dia, LLC.]]}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=3034501}}\n\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 2010\u20132019}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dyer, Natalia}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:New York University Gallatin School of Individualized Study alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2405:204:3399:8425:6492:50ab:34ae:acfd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natalia_Dyer"}
{"title_page": "Shiba Inu", "text_new": "<!-- Do not edit this page to include the Doge meme per [[WP:TRIVIA]] and extensive discussion not to include the meme on this page's talk section  -->\n{{Infobox dog breed \n| akcgroup = Non-Sporting\n| akcstd = http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/#standard\n| altname = Japanese Shiba Inu<br>Japanese Small Size Dog<br>Japanese Brushwood Dog<br>Japanese Turf Dog<br>Shiba Ken\n| image = Taka_Shiba.jpg\n| image_caption = 3-year-old Red Shiba Inu\n| name = Shiba Inu\n| nickname = <!--Since 2014, there has been a consensus not to include 'doge' on this list. Please do not add 'doge' unless a new consensus has been reached--> Shiba<br>Shibe\n| country = [[Japan]]\n| prefecture = [[Nagano]]\n<!-- Classification & standards -->\n| ankcgroup = Group 6 (Utility)\n| ankcstd = http://www.ankc.aust.com/shibainu.html\n| ckcgroup = Group 6 - Non-Sporting\n| ckcstd = http://www.ckc.ca/en/Portals/0/pdf/breeds/SII.pdf\n| fcigroup = 5 Spitz and Primitive dogs\n| fcinum = 257\n| fcisection = 5 Asian Spitz and related breeds\n| fcistd = http://www.fci.be/uploaded_files/257gb99_en.doc\n| kcukgroup = Utility\n| kcukstd = http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/163\n| ukcgroup = [[Northern Breed Group|Northern Breed]]\n| ukcstd = http://www.ukcdogs.com/Web.nsf/Breeds/NorthernBreed/Shiba07012009\n<!-- ---Traits--- -->\n| maleweight = {{convert|10|kg|abbr=on}}\n| femaleweight = {{convert|8|kg|abbr=on}}\n| maleheight = {{convert|35|to|43|cm|abbr=on}}\n| femaleheight = {{convert|33|to|41|cm|abbr=on}}\n| coat = double\n| color = Red, sesame, black and tan, or cream\n| litter_size = 3 puppies on average\n| life_span = 12\u201315 years\n<!-- Notes -->\n| note   = <ref name=canismajor /><ref name=AKCstandard/> It is similar to the [[Akita dog|Akita]], though much smaller in stature.\n}}\n{{infobox Chinese\n|pic=Shiba Inu (Chinese characters).svg\n|piccap=\"Shiba Inu\" in ''[[kanji]]''\n|picupright=0.325\n|kanji=\u67f4\u72ac\n|hiragana=\u3057\u3070 \u3044\u306c\n|romaji=shiba inu\n}}\nThe {{nihongo|'''Shiba Inu'''|[[wikt:\u67f4\u72ac|\u67f4\u72ac]]||extra={{IPA-ja|\u0255iba\u0320 in\u026f\u031f\u1d5d|lang}}}} is a [[Japan|Japanese]] [[dog breed|breed]] of [[hunting dog]]. A small-to-medium breed, it is the smallest of the six original and distinct [[spitz]] breeds of [[dog]] native to Japan.<ref name=canismajor>{{cite web | url=http://www.canismajor.com/dog/shiba.html | title=Dog Owners Guide: Shiba Inu | accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref> \n\nA small, agile dog that copes very well with mountainous terrain and hiking trails, the Shiba Inu was originally bred for hunting.<ref name=canismajor /><ref name=AKCstandard>{{cite web |title=Shiba Inu Breed Standard |publisher=American Kennel Club |url=http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/#standard |accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref> It looks similar to and is often mistaken for other Japanese dog breeds like the [[Akita Inu]] or [[Hokkaido (dog)|Hokkaido]], but the Shiba Inu is a different breed with a distinct blood line, temperament, and smaller size than other Japanese dog breeds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkc.or.jp/modules/worlddogs/category.php?categoryID=5|title=Japanese Kennel Club Classification|publisher=Jkc.or.jp|accessdate=1 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026031835/http://www.jkc.or.jp/modules/worlddogs/category.php?categoryID=5|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japanesedog.org/shiba-inu/|title=Shiba inu|publisher=Japanesedog.org|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=genstruct>{{cite journal |last1=Parker |first1=Heidi G. |last2=Kim |first2=Lisa V. |last3=Sutter |first3=Nathan B. |last4=Carlson |first4=Scott |last5=Lorentzen |first5=Travis D. |last6=Malek |first6=Tiffany B. |last7=Johnson |first7=Gary S. |last8=DeFrance |first8=Hawkins B. |last9=Ostrander |first9=Elaine A. |last10=Kruglyak |first10=Leonid |date=2004-05-21 |title=Genetic Structure of the Purebred Domestic Dog |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=304 |issue=5674 |pmid=15155949 |doi=10.1126/science.1097406 |url=https://www.princeton.edu/genomics/kruglyak/publication/PDF/2004_Parker_Genetic.pdf |pages=1160\u20134 |access-date=2013-04-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905170142/https://www.princeton.edu/genomics/kruglyak/publication/PDF/2004_Parker_Genetic.pdf |archive-date=2014-09-05 |url-status=dead |bibcode=2004Sci...304.1160P }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Shiba inu at the entrance of a house, -Japan 2010 a.jpg|thumb|left|A Shiba Inu in [[Kagawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]]]]\n''Inu'' is the Japanese word for dog, but the origin of the prefix \"Shiba\" is less clear. The word ''shiba'' means \"brushwood\" in Japanese, and refers to a type of tree or shrub whose leaves turn red in the fall.<ref name=Total>{{cite book |last1=Haskett |first1=Gretchen |last2=Houser |first2=Susan |title=The Total Shiba |publisher=Alpine Publications |location=Loveland, CO |year=1997 |isbn=1-57779-049-9}}</ref> This leads some to believe that the Shiba was named with this in mind, either because the dogs were used to hunt in wild shrubs, or because the most common color of the Shiba Inu is a red color similar to that of the shrubs. However, in an old Nagano dialect, the word ''shiba'' also had the meaning of \"small\", thus this might be a reference to the dog's diminutive stature.<ref name=\"Total\"/> Therefore, the Shiba Inu is sometimes translated as \"Little Brushwood Dog\".<ref name=\"canismajor\"/>\n\n==Appearance==\n\n[[File:Shiba Inu cream.jpg|thumb|left|A \"white\" (also called \"cream\") Shiba Inu]]\nThe Shiba's frame is compact with well-developed muscles.<ref name=\"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\">[http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/#standard \"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"], 'The American Kennel Club', retrieved 14 May 2014</ref> Males are {{convert|35|to|43|cm|abbr=on}} at the [[withers]]. Females are {{convert|33|to|41|cm|abbr=on}}. The preferred size is the middle of the range for each sex. Average weight at preferred size is approximately {{convert|10.5|kg|abbr=on}} for males, {{convert|8|kg|abbr=on}} for females. Bones are moderate. They are so cute and we all love them.\n\nThe Shiba is double coated, with the outer coat being stiff and straight and the undercoat soft and thick. Fur is short and even on the fox-like face, ears, and legs. Guard hairs stand off the body and are about {{convert|1+1/2|to|2|in|cm|0|order=flip|abbr=on}} long at the withers. The purpose of the guard hairs is to protect their underlying skin and to repel rain or snow. Tail hair is slightly longer and stands open in a brush. Their tails are a defining characteristic and makes them stand apart from other dog breeds. Their tails help to protect them from the harsh winter weather.  When they sleep, Shiba Inus curl up and use their tails to shield their face and nose in order to protect their sensitive areas from the cold.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}} Shibas may be red, orange, yellow, black and tan, or sesame (red with black-tipped hairs),<ref name=\"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"/> with a cream, buff, or grey undercoat. They may also be white (cream), though this color is considered a \"major fault\" by the American Kennel Club and should never be intentionally bred in a show dog, as the required markings known as {{nihongo|\"urajiro\"|\u88cf\u767d}} are not visible; \"Urajiro\" literally translates to \"underside white\".<ref name=AKCstandard/> Conversely, a white (cream) coat is perfectly acceptable according to the British Kennel Club breed standard.<ref name=KCstandard>{{cite web |title=Japanese Shiba Inu Breed Standard |publisher=The Kennel Club Limited |url=http://www.the-kennel-club.org.uk/services/public/breed/standard.aspx?id=4110 |accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe ''urajiro'' (cream to white ventral color) is required in the following areas on all coat colors: on the sides of the muzzle, on the cheeks, inside the ears, on the underjaw and upper throat inside of legs, on the abdomen, around the vent and the ventral side of the tail. On reds: commonly on the throat, forechest, and chest. On blacks and sesames: commonly as a triangular mark on both sides of the forechest.<ref name=urajiro>{{cite web |title=NSCA: Urajiro |url=http://www.shibas.org/newstand/urajiro.html |accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Temperament==\n[[File:Shiba Inu 600.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Sesame Shiba Inu]]\nShibas tend to exhibit an independent nature.<ref name=\"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"/> From the Japanese breed standard:\n\n<blockquote>The dog has a spirited boldness and is fiercely proud with a good nature and a feeling of artlessness. The Shiba is able to move quickly with nimble, elastic steps.</blockquote>\n\nThe terms {{nihongo|\"spirited boldness\"|\u608d\u5a01|kan'i}}, {{nihongo|\"good nature\"|\u826f\u6027|ry\u014dsei}}, and {{nihongo|\"artlessness\"|\u7d20\u6734|soboku}} have subtle interpretations that have been the subject of much commentary.<ref name=detailedstudy>Miriam Clews (Ed.). ''The Japanese Shiba Inu: A detailed study of the Shiba''.</ref>\n\nThe Shiba is a relatively fastidious breed and feels the need to maintain itself in a clean state. They can often be seen licking their paws and legs, much as cats do. They generally go out of their way to keep their coats clean. Because of their fastidious and proud nature, Shiba puppies are easy to housebreak and in many cases will housebreak themselves. Having their owner simply place them outside after meal times and naps is generally enough to teach the Shiba the appropriate method of toileting.<ref name=cratetraining>{{cite web | url=http://www.shibas.org/newstand/living.html | title=An Introduction to the Shiba Inu (part 2) | accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\nA distinguishing characteristic of the breed is the so-called \"shiba scream\". When sufficiently provoked or unhappy, the dog will produce a loud, high-pitched scream. This can occur when attempting to handle the dog in a way that it deems unacceptable.<ref name=canismajor /><ref name=ShibaScream>{{cite web | url=http://www.northeastshibarescue.com/traits.html | title=Shiba Inu Traits | accessdate=August 20, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070810225914/http://www.northeastshibarescue.com/traits.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = August 10, 2007}}</ref><ref name=MisanthropicShiba>{{cite web |url=http://www.shibainus.ca/ | title=The Misanthropic Shiba | accessdate= August 21, 2007}}</ref> The animal may also emit a very similar sound during periods of great joy, such as the return of the owner after an extended absence, or the arrival of a favored human guest.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Shiba inu blacktan.jpg|thumb|left|upright|200 px|Black and tan Shiba Inu with urajiro]]\n\nThe Shiba Inu has been identified as a [[Dog breed#Basal breeds|basal breed]] that predates the emergence of the modern breeds in the 19th Century.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Larson, G|year=2012|title=Rethinking dog domestication by integrating genetics, archeology, and biogeography|doi=10.1073/pnas.1203005109|pmid=22615366|pmc=3384140|volume=109|issue=23|journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A.|pages=8878\u201383|bibcode=2012PNAS..109.8878L}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the Shiba Inu was bred to hunt and [[Hunting dog|flush]] small game, such as birds and rabbit. Shiba lived in the mountainous areas of the [[Ch\u016bbu region]]. During the [[Meiji Restoration]], western dog breeds were imported and crosses between these and native Japanese breeds became popular. From 1912 to 1926, almost no pure Shiba remained. From around 1928, hunters and intellectuals began to show interest in the protection of the remaining pure Shiba;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jkc.or.jp/modules/worlddogs/entry.php?entryID=105&categoryID=5|title=\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u72ac : 5G \u539f\u59cb\u7684\u306a\u72ac\u30fb\u30b9\u30d4\u30c3\u30c4 : \u3057 : \u67f4 - SHIBA|website=www.jkc.or.jp |access-date=May 16, 2018 |language=Japanese |trans-title=World dogs: 5G primitive dog \u00b7 Spitz: Shi: Shiba - SHIBA}}</ref>  however, despite efforts to preserve the breed, the Shiba nearly became extinct during [[World War II]]<ref name=\"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"/> due to a combination of food shortage and a post-war [[Canine distemper|distemper]] epidemic.<ref name=canismajor /> All subsequent dogs were bred from the only three surviving bloodlines.<ref name=5stardog>{{cite web | url=http://www.5stardog.com/dog-breeds-shiba-inu.asp | title=Shiba Inu Dog Breeds | accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref> These bloodlines were the Shinshu Shiba from [[Nagano Prefecture]], the Mino Shiba from the former [[Mino Province]] in the south of present-day [[Gifu Prefecture]], and the San'in Shiba from [[Tottori Prefecture|Tottori]] and [[Shimane Prefecture]]s.<ref name=Total/> The Shinshu Shibas possessed a solid undercoat, with a dense layer of guard-hairs, and were small and red in color. \n\n[[File:Fm shiba inu puppy.jpg|thumb|right|Shiba Inu puppy]]\nThe Mino Shibas tended to have thick, prick ears, and possessed a sickle tail, rather than the common curled tail found on most modern Shibas. The San'in Shibas were larger than most modern shibas, and tended to be black, without the common tan and white accents found on modern black-and-tan shibas.<ref name=\"Total\"/> When the study of Japanese dogs was formalized in the early and mid-20th century, these three strains were combined into one overall breed, the Shiba Inu.<ref name=\"Total\"/> The first Japanese breed standard for the Shiba, the Nippo Standard, was published in 1934. In December 1936, the Shiba Inu was recognized as a Natural Monument of Japan through the Cultural Properties Act, largely due to the efforts of Nippo ([[Nihon Ken Hozonkai]]), the Association for the Preservation of the Japanese Dog.<ref name=\"Total\"/><ref>{{cite book\n| last = Atkinson\n| first = Maureen\n| title = The Complete Shiba Inu\n| publisher = [[Howell Book House]]\n| year = 1998\n| page = 11\n| isbn = 0-87605-177-8}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, an armed service family brought the first Shiba Inu to the [[United States]].<ref name=5stardog /> In 1979, the first recorded litter was born in the United States.<ref name=5stardog /> The Shiba was recognized by the [[American Kennel Club]] in 1992 and added to the AKC [[Non-Sporting Group]] in 1993.<ref name=canismajor /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/#standard|title=Shiba Inu Dog Breed Information|first=American Kennel|last=Club|publisher=}}</ref> It is now primarily kept as a pet both in Japan and abroad.<ref name=k9web>{{cite web |last=Holden |first=Jacey |title=Shiba Inus |url=http://www.k9web.com/dog-faqs/breeds/shibas.html |accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref> According to the [[American Kennel Club]], the Shiba Inu is the number one companion dog in Japan. In the United States, the growing popularity of the Shiba Inu is evident as the [[American Kennel Club]] Registration Statistics ranked the breed in 44th place in 2016; a rise from 50th place in 2012.<ref>[http://www.akc.org/news/the-most-popular-dog-breeds-in-america/ American Kennel Club 2013 Dog Registration Statistics Historical Comparisons & Notable Trends], ''The American Kennel Club'', Retrieved 17 February 2018</ref>\n\n==Health==\n[[File:Shiba inu taiki.jpg|thumb|Shiba Inu portrait]]\nOverall, the Shiba Inu is a healthy dog breed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dogtime.com/dog-breeds/shiba-inu#|title=Shiba Inu|publisher=dogtime.com|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smalldogplace.com/shiba-inu.html|title=The Shiba Inu|publisher=smalldogplace.com|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pikimal.com/dog-breed/shiba-inu-2|title=Shiba Inu|publisher=pikimal.com|accessdate=1 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411134112/http://pikimal.com/dog-breed/shiba-inu-2|archive-date=11 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dogs.lovetoknow.com/wiki/Shiba_Inu|title=About the Shiba Inu|publisher=dogs.lovetoknow.com|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref>\nHealth conditions known to affect this breed are [[allergy|allergies]], [[glaucoma]], [[cataract]]s, [[Hip dysplasia (canine)|hip dysplasia]], [[entropion]], and [[luxating patella]].<ref name=shibahealth>{{cite web |last=Holden |first=Jacey |title=An Overview of Health Problems in the Shiba Inu |url=http://www.shibas.org/newstand/health.html |accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref> \nPeriodic joint examinations are recommended throughout the dog's life.  Eye tests should be performed yearly as eye problems can develop over time. By two years of age, Shiba Inus may be considered fully free from joint problems, if none have been discovered, since at this age the skeleton is fully developed.\n\nAs with most dog breeds, Shibas should be walked or otherwise exercised daily.<ref>[http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/care/#exercise \"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"], 'The American Kennel Club', retrieved 13 May 2014</ref>\n\n===Life span===\nTheir average life expectancy is from 12 to 15 years. Exercise, especially daily walks, is preferred for this breed to live a long and healthy life.<ref name=\"5stardog\"/> The oldest known Shiba, [[Pusuke]], died at age 26 in early December 2011. Pusuke was the oldest dog alive at the time and lived three years less than the world record for longest living dog.\n\n===Grooming===\nThese dogs are very clean, so grooming needs will likely be minimal. They naturally tend to hate to be wet or bathed, thus, it is very important to start accustomed when they are young. A Shiba Inu's coat is coarse; short to medium length with the outer coat being {{convert|1|to|1+1/4|in|cm|order=flip|abbr=on}} long, and is naturally waterproof so there is little need for regular bathing. They also have a thick undercoat that can protect them from temperatures well below freezing. However, shedding, also known as blowing coat, can be a nuisance. Shedding is heaviest during the seasonal change and particularly during the summer season, but daily brushing can temper this problem. It is recommended that owners never shave or cut the coat of a Shiba Inu, as the coat is needed to protect them from both cold and hot temperatures.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shiba Inu Training - Grooming |url=http://www.shibainutraining.com/grooming/ |accessdate=1 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131118104315/http://www.shibainutraining.com/grooming/ |archive-date=18 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\" perrow=\"5\" caption=\"Shiba Inu\">\nFile:Siro-shiba.JPG|A cream coated Shiba Inu\nFile:Taro (black and tan, reu) - Chiko (rood, reu) - Ichigo (rood, teef).jpg|Two red Shiba Inus with a black and tan Shiba Inu\nFile:Shiba Inu.jpg|A red Shiba Inu\nFile:Sumo ondeck July06.jpg|A red Shiba Inu puppy\nFile:Shiba-inu Magyarorsz\u00e1g.jpg|2-year-old Shiba Inu\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Dogs|Japan}}\n* [[Doge (meme)]]\n* [[Mameshiba (character)|Mameshiba]]\n* [[Dogecoin]], which features a likeness of the breed.\n* [[Japan Kennel Club]]\n* [[Shiba Inu Puppy Cam]]\n* [[Nihon Ken Hozonkai]]\n<!--====================================================================================================================\n    | PLEASE DO NOT PLACE DOGE MEME HERE, TRIVIA DOESN'T BELONG IN ARTICLE \n============================================================================================================================-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{dmoz|Recreation/Pets/Dogs/Breeds/NonSporting-Utility_Group/Shiba_Inu/}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD PRIVATE BREEDERS OR ADVERTISING; IT WILL BE REMOVED -->\n<!--Editors: breed registry, club, rescue, and kennel information links are placed on DMOZ, not here-->\n\n{{Japanese dogs}}\n{{Spitz}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Spitz breeds]]\n[[Category:FCI breeds]]\n[[Category:Dog breeds originating in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Do not edit this page to include the Doge meme per [[WP:TRIVIA]] and extensive discussion not to include the meme on this page's talk section  -->\n{{Infobox dog breed \n| akcgroup = Non-Sporting\n| akcstd = http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/#standard\n| altname = Japanese Shiba Inu<br>Japanese Small Size Dog<br>Japanese Brushwood Dog<br>Japanese Turf Dog<br>Shiba Ken\n| image = Taka_Shiba.jpg\n| image_caption = 3-year-old Red Shiba Inu\n| name = Shiba Inu\n| nickname = <!--Since 2014, there has been a consensus not to include 'doge' on this list. Please do not add 'doge' unless a new consensus has been reached--> Shiba<br>Shibe\n| country = [[Japan]]\n| prefecture = [[Nagano]]\n<!-- Classification & standards -->\n| ankcgroup = Group 6 (Utility)\n| ankcstd = http://www.ankc.aust.com/shibainu.html\n| ckcgroup = Group 6 - Non-Sporting\n| ckcstd = http://www.ckc.ca/en/Portals/0/pdf/breeds/SII.pdf\n| fcigroup = 5 Spitz and Primitive dogs\n| fcinum = 257\n| fcisection = 5 Asian Spitz and related breeds\n| fcistd = http://www.fci.be/uploaded_files/257gb99_en.doc\n| kcukgroup = Utility\n| kcukstd = http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/163\n| ukcgroup = [[Northern Breed Group|Northern Breed]]\n| ukcstd = http://www.ukcdogs.com/Web.nsf/Breeds/NorthernBreed/Shiba07012009\n<!-- ---Traits--- -->\n| maleweight = {{convert|10|kg|abbr=on}}\n| femaleweight = {{convert|8|kg|abbr=on}}\n| maleheight = {{convert|35|to|43|cm|abbr=on}}\n| femaleheight = {{convert|33|to|41|cm|abbr=on}}\n| coat = double\n| color = Red, sesame, black and tan, or cream\n| litter_size = 3 puppies on average\n| life_span = 12\u201315 years\n<!-- Notes -->\n| note   = <ref name=canismajor /><ref name=AKCstandard/> It is similar to the [[Akita dog|Akita]], though much smaller in stature.\n}}\n{{infobox Chinese\n|pic=Shiba Inu (Chinese characters).svg\n|piccap=\"Shiba Inu\" in ''[[kanji]]''\n|picupright=0.325\n|kanji=\u67f4\u72ac\n|hiragana=\u3057\u3070 \u3044\u306c\n|romaji=shiba inu\n}}\nThe {{nihongo|'''Shiba Inu'''|[[wikt:\u67f4\u72ac|\u67f4\u72ac]]||extra={{IPA-ja|\u0255iba\u0320 in\u026f\u031f\u1d5d|lang}}}} is a [[Japan|Japanese]] [[dog breed|breed]] of [[hunting dog]]. A small-to-medium breed, it is the smallest of the six original and distinct [[spitz]] breeds of [[dog]] native to Japan.<ref name=canismajor>{{cite web | url=http://www.canismajor.com/dog/shiba.html | title=Dog Owners Guide: Shiba Inu | accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref> \n\nA small, agile dog that copes very well with mountainous terrain and hiking trails, the Shiba Inu was originally bred for hunting.<ref name=canismajor /><ref name=AKCstandard>{{cite web |title=Shiba Inu Breed Standard |publisher=American Kennel Club |url=http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/#standard |accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref> It looks similar to and is often mistaken for other Japanese dog breeds like the [[Akita Inu]] or [[Hokkaido (dog)|Hokkaido]], but the Shiba Inu is a different breed with a distinct blood line, temperament, and smaller size than other Japanese dog breeds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jkc.or.jp/modules/worlddogs/category.php?categoryID=5|title=Japanese Kennel Club Classification|publisher=Jkc.or.jp|accessdate=1 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026031835/http://www.jkc.or.jp/modules/worlddogs/category.php?categoryID=5|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japanesedog.org/shiba-inu/|title=Shiba inu|publisher=Japanesedog.org|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=genstruct>{{cite journal |last1=Parker |first1=Heidi G. |last2=Kim |first2=Lisa V. |last3=Sutter |first3=Nathan B. |last4=Carlson |first4=Scott |last5=Lorentzen |first5=Travis D. |last6=Malek |first6=Tiffany B. |last7=Johnson |first7=Gary S. |last8=DeFrance |first8=Hawkins B. |last9=Ostrander |first9=Elaine A. |last10=Kruglyak |first10=Leonid |date=2004-05-21 |title=Genetic Structure of the Purebred Domestic Dog |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=304 |issue=5674 |pmid=15155949 |doi=10.1126/science.1097406 |url=https://www.princeton.edu/genomics/kruglyak/publication/PDF/2004_Parker_Genetic.pdf |pages=1160\u20134 |access-date=2013-04-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905170142/https://www.princeton.edu/genomics/kruglyak/publication/PDF/2004_Parker_Genetic.pdf |archive-date=2014-09-05 |url-status=dead |bibcode=2004Sci...304.1160P }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Shiba inu at the entrance of a house, -Japan 2010 a.jpg|thumb|left|A Shiba Inu in [[Kagawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]]]]\n''Inu'' is the Japanese word for dog, but the origin of the prefix \"Shiba\" is less clear. The word ''shiba'' means \"brushwood\" in Japanese, and refers to a type of tree or shrub whose leaves turn red in the fall.<ref name=Total>{{cite book |last1=Haskett |first1=Gretchen |last2=Houser |first2=Susan |title=The Total Shiba |publisher=Alpine Publications |location=Loveland, CO |year=1997 |isbn=1-57779-049-9}}</ref> This leads some to believe that the Shiba was named with this in mind, either because the dogs were used to hunt in wild shrubs, or because the most common color of the Shiba Inu is a red color similar to that of the shrubs. However, in an old Nagano dialect, the word ''shiba'' also had the meaning of \"small\", thus this might be a reference to the dog's diminutive stature.<ref name=\"Total\"/> Therefore, the Shiba Inu is sometimes translated as \"Little Brushwood Dog\".<ref name=\"canismajor\"/>\n\n==Appearance==\n\n[[File:Shiba Inu cream.jpg|thumb|left|A \"white\" (also called \"cream\") Shiba Inu]]\nThe Shiba's frame is compact with well-developed muscles.<ref name=\"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\">[http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/#standard \"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"], 'The American Kennel Club', retrieved 14 May 2014</ref> Males are {{convert|35|to|43|cm|abbr=on}} at the [[withers]]. Females are {{convert|33|to|41|cm|abbr=on}}. The preferred size is the middle of the range for each sex. Average weight at preferred size is approximately {{convert|10.5|kg|abbr=on}} for males, {{convert|8|kg|abbr=on}} for females. Bones are moderate.\n\nThe Shiba is double coated, with the outer coat being stiff and straight and the undercoat soft and thick. Fur is short and even on the fox-like face, ears, and legs. Guard hairs stand off the body and are about {{convert|1+1/2|to|2|in|cm|0|order=flip|abbr=on}} long at the withers. The purpose of the guard hairs is to protect their underlying skin and to repel rain or snow. Tail hair is slightly longer and stands open in a brush. Their tails are a defining characteristic and makes them stand apart from other dog breeds. Their tails help to protect them from the harsh winter weather.  When they sleep, Shiba Inus curl up and use their tails to shield their face and nose in order to protect their sensitive areas from the cold.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}} Shibas may be red, orange, yellow, black and tan, or sesame (red with black-tipped hairs),<ref name=\"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"/> with a cream, buff, or grey undercoat. They may also be white (cream), though this color is considered a \"major fault\" by the American Kennel Club and should never be intentionally bred in a show dog, as the required markings known as {{nihongo|\"urajiro\"|\u88cf\u767d}} are not visible; \"Urajiro\" literally translates to \"underside white\".<ref name=AKCstandard/> Conversely, a white (cream) coat is perfectly acceptable according to the British Kennel Club breed standard.<ref name=KCstandard>{{cite web |title=Japanese Shiba Inu Breed Standard |publisher=The Kennel Club Limited |url=http://www.the-kennel-club.org.uk/services/public/breed/standard.aspx?id=4110 |accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe ''urajiro'' (cream to white ventral color) is required in the following areas on all coat colors: on the sides of the muzzle, on the cheeks, inside the ears, on the underjaw and upper throat inside of legs, on the abdomen, around the vent and the ventral side of the tail. On reds: commonly on the throat, forechest, and chest. On blacks and sesames: commonly as a triangular mark on both sides of the forechest.<ref name=urajiro>{{cite web |title=NSCA: Urajiro |url=http://www.shibas.org/newstand/urajiro.html |accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Temperament==\n[[File:Shiba Inu 600.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Sesame Shiba Inu]]\nShibas tend to exhibit an independent nature.<ref name=\"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"/> From the Japanese breed standard:\n\n<blockquote>The dog has a spirited boldness and is fiercely proud with a good nature and a feeling of artlessness. The Shiba is able to move quickly with nimble, elastic steps.</blockquote>\n\nThe terms {{nihongo|\"spirited boldness\"|\u608d\u5a01|kan'i}}, {{nihongo|\"good nature\"|\u826f\u6027|ry\u014dsei}}, and {{nihongo|\"artlessness\"|\u7d20\u6734|soboku}} have subtle interpretations that have been the subject of much commentary.<ref name=detailedstudy>Miriam Clews (Ed.). ''The Japanese Shiba Inu: A detailed study of the Shiba''.</ref>\n\nThe Shiba is a relatively fastidious breed and feels the need to maintain itself in a clean state. They can often be seen licking their paws and legs, much as cats do. They generally go out of their way to keep their coats clean. Because of their fastidious and proud nature, Shiba puppies are easy to housebreak and in many cases will housebreak themselves. Having their owner simply place them outside after meal times and naps is generally enough to teach the Shiba the appropriate method of toileting.<ref name=cratetraining>{{cite web | url=http://www.shibas.org/newstand/living.html | title=An Introduction to the Shiba Inu (part 2) | accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\nA distinguishing characteristic of the breed is the so-called \"shiba scream\". When sufficiently provoked or unhappy, the dog will produce a loud, high-pitched scream. This can occur when attempting to handle the dog in a way that it deems unacceptable.<ref name=canismajor /><ref name=ShibaScream>{{cite web | url=http://www.northeastshibarescue.com/traits.html | title=Shiba Inu Traits | accessdate=August 20, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070810225914/http://www.northeastshibarescue.com/traits.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = August 10, 2007}}</ref><ref name=MisanthropicShiba>{{cite web |url=http://www.shibainus.ca/ | title=The Misanthropic Shiba | accessdate= August 21, 2007}}</ref> The animal may also emit a very similar sound during periods of great joy, such as the return of the owner after an extended absence, or the arrival of a favored human guest.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Shiba inu blacktan.jpg|thumb|left|upright|200 px|Black and tan Shiba Inu with urajiro]]\n\nThe Shiba Inu has been identified as a [[Dog breed#Basal breeds|basal breed]] that predates the emergence of the modern breeds in the 19th Century.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Larson, G|year=2012|title=Rethinking dog domestication by integrating genetics, archeology, and biogeography|doi=10.1073/pnas.1203005109|pmid=22615366|pmc=3384140|volume=109|issue=23|journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A.|pages=8878\u201383|bibcode=2012PNAS..109.8878L}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the Shiba Inu was bred to hunt and [[Hunting dog|flush]] small game, such as birds and rabbit. Shiba lived in the mountainous areas of the [[Ch\u016bbu region]]. During the [[Meiji Restoration]], western dog breeds were imported and crosses between these and native Japanese breeds became popular. From 1912 to 1926, almost no pure Shiba remained. From around 1928, hunters and intellectuals began to show interest in the protection of the remaining pure Shiba;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jkc.or.jp/modules/worlddogs/entry.php?entryID=105&categoryID=5|title=\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u72ac : 5G \u539f\u59cb\u7684\u306a\u72ac\u30fb\u30b9\u30d4\u30c3\u30c4 : \u3057 : \u67f4 - SHIBA|website=www.jkc.or.jp |access-date=May 16, 2018 |language=Japanese |trans-title=World dogs: 5G primitive dog \u00b7 Spitz: Shi: Shiba - SHIBA}}</ref>  however, despite efforts to preserve the breed, the Shiba nearly became extinct during [[World War II]]<ref name=\"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"/> due to a combination of food shortage and a post-war [[Canine distemper|distemper]] epidemic.<ref name=canismajor /> All subsequent dogs were bred from the only three surviving bloodlines.<ref name=5stardog>{{cite web | url=http://www.5stardog.com/dog-breeds-shiba-inu.asp | title=Shiba Inu Dog Breeds | accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref> These bloodlines were the Shinshu Shiba from [[Nagano Prefecture]], the Mino Shiba from the former [[Mino Province]] in the south of present-day [[Gifu Prefecture]], and the San'in Shiba from [[Tottori Prefecture|Tottori]] and [[Shimane Prefecture]]s.<ref name=Total/> The Shinshu Shibas possessed a solid undercoat, with a dense layer of guard-hairs, and were small and red in color. \n\n[[File:Fm shiba inu puppy.jpg|thumb|right|Shiba Inu puppy]]\nThe Mino Shibas tended to have thick, prick ears, and possessed a sickle tail, rather than the common curled tail found on most modern Shibas. The San'in Shibas were larger than most modern shibas, and tended to be black, without the common tan and white accents found on modern black-and-tan shibas.<ref name=\"Total\"/> When the study of Japanese dogs was formalized in the early and mid-20th century, these three strains were combined into one overall breed, the Shiba Inu.<ref name=\"Total\"/> The first Japanese breed standard for the Shiba, the Nippo Standard, was published in 1934. In December 1936, the Shiba Inu was recognized as a Natural Monument of Japan through the Cultural Properties Act, largely due to the efforts of Nippo ([[Nihon Ken Hozonkai]]), the Association for the Preservation of the Japanese Dog.<ref name=\"Total\"/><ref>{{cite book\n| last = Atkinson\n| first = Maureen\n| title = The Complete Shiba Inu\n| publisher = [[Howell Book House]]\n| year = 1998\n| page = 11\n| isbn = 0-87605-177-8}}</ref>\n\nIn 1954, an armed service family brought the first Shiba Inu to the [[United States]].<ref name=5stardog /> In 1979, the first recorded litter was born in the United States.<ref name=5stardog /> The Shiba was recognized by the [[American Kennel Club]] in 1992 and added to the AKC [[Non-Sporting Group]] in 1993.<ref name=canismajor /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/#standard|title=Shiba Inu Dog Breed Information|first=American Kennel|last=Club|publisher=}}</ref> It is now primarily kept as a pet both in Japan and abroad.<ref name=k9web>{{cite web |last=Holden |first=Jacey |title=Shiba Inus |url=http://www.k9web.com/dog-faqs/breeds/shibas.html |accessdate=August 23, 2007}}</ref> According to the [[American Kennel Club]], the Shiba Inu is the number one companion dog in Japan. In the United States, the growing popularity of the Shiba Inu is evident as the [[American Kennel Club]] Registration Statistics ranked the breed in 44th place in 2016; a rise from 50th place in 2012.<ref>[http://www.akc.org/news/the-most-popular-dog-breeds-in-america/ American Kennel Club 2013 Dog Registration Statistics Historical Comparisons & Notable Trends], ''The American Kennel Club'', Retrieved 17 February 2018</ref>\n\n==Health==\n[[File:Shiba inu taiki.jpg|thumb|Shiba Inu portrait]]\nOverall, the Shiba Inu is a healthy dog breed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dogtime.com/dog-breeds/shiba-inu#|title=Shiba Inu|publisher=dogtime.com|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smalldogplace.com/shiba-inu.html|title=The Shiba Inu|publisher=smalldogplace.com|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pikimal.com/dog-breed/shiba-inu-2|title=Shiba Inu|publisher=pikimal.com|accessdate=1 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411134112/http://pikimal.com/dog-breed/shiba-inu-2|archive-date=11 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dogs.lovetoknow.com/wiki/Shiba_Inu|title=About the Shiba Inu|publisher=dogs.lovetoknow.com|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref>\nHealth conditions known to affect this breed are [[allergy|allergies]], [[glaucoma]], [[cataract]]s, [[Hip dysplasia (canine)|hip dysplasia]], [[entropion]], and [[luxating patella]].<ref name=shibahealth>{{cite web |last=Holden |first=Jacey |title=An Overview of Health Problems in the Shiba Inu |url=http://www.shibas.org/newstand/health.html |accessdate=August 20, 2007}}</ref> \nPeriodic joint examinations are recommended throughout the dog's life.  Eye tests should be performed yearly as eye problems can develop over time. By two years of age, Shiba Inus may be considered fully free from joint problems, if none have been discovered, since at this age the skeleton is fully developed.\n\nAs with most dog breeds, Shibas should be walked or otherwise exercised daily.<ref>[http://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/shiba-inu/care/#exercise \"Get to Know the Shiba Inu\"], 'The American Kennel Club', retrieved 13 May 2014</ref>\n\n===Life span===\nTheir average life expectancy is from 12 to 15 years. Exercise, especially daily walks, is preferred for this breed to live a long and healthy life.<ref name=\"5stardog\"/> The oldest known Shiba, [[Pusuke]], died at age 26 in early December 2011. Pusuke was the oldest dog alive at the time and lived three years less than the world record for longest living dog.\n\n===Grooming===\nThese dogs are very clean, so grooming needs will likely be minimal. They naturally tend to hate to be wet or bathed, thus, it is very important to start accustomed when they are young. A Shiba Inu's coat is coarse; short to medium length with the outer coat being {{convert|1|to|1+1/4|in|cm|order=flip|abbr=on}} long, and is naturally waterproof so there is little need for regular bathing. They also have a thick undercoat that can protect them from temperatures well below freezing. However, shedding, also known as blowing coat, can be a nuisance. Shedding is heaviest during the seasonal change and particularly during the summer season, but daily brushing can temper this problem. It is recommended that owners never shave or cut the coat of a Shiba Inu, as the coat is needed to protect them from both cold and hot temperatures.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shiba Inu Training - Grooming |url=http://www.shibainutraining.com/grooming/ |accessdate=1 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131118104315/http://www.shibainutraining.com/grooming/ |archive-date=18 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\" perrow=\"5\" caption=\"Shiba Inu\">\nFile:Siro-shiba.JPG|A cream coated Shiba Inu\nFile:Taro (black and tan, reu) - Chiko (rood, reu) - Ichigo (rood, teef).jpg|Two red Shiba Inus with a black and tan Shiba Inu\nFile:Shiba Inu.jpg|A red Shiba Inu\nFile:Sumo ondeck July06.jpg|A red Shiba Inu puppy\nFile:Shiba-inu Magyarorsz\u00e1g.jpg|2-year-old Shiba Inu\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Dogs|Japan}}\n* [[Doge (meme)]]\n* [[Mameshiba (character)|Mameshiba]]\n* [[Dogecoin]], which features a likeness of the breed.\n* [[Japan Kennel Club]]\n* [[Shiba Inu Puppy Cam]]\n* [[Nihon Ken Hozonkai]]\n<!--====================================================================================================================\n    | PLEASE DO NOT PLACE DOGE MEME HERE, TRIVIA DOESN'T BELONG IN ARTICLE \n============================================================================================================================-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{dmoz|Recreation/Pets/Dogs/Breeds/NonSporting-Utility_Group/Shiba_Inu/}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD PRIVATE BREEDERS OR ADVERTISING; IT WILL BE REMOVED -->\n<!--Editors: breed registry, club, rescue, and kennel information links are placed on DMOZ, not here-->\n\n{{Japanese dogs}}\n{{Spitz}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Spitz breeds]]\n[[Category:FCI breeds]]\n[[Category:Dog breeds originating in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Df,rb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shiba_Inu"}
