ps://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/canada/rcmp-say-in-excess-of-19-victims-in-n-s-rampage-1.4903398|title=RCMP say 'in excess of 19 victims' in N.S. rampage|date=2020-04-20|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The attack took place from the late hours of April 18 to the evening of April 19 and ended when Wortman was shot dead by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]].{{cn}}\n \nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=At Least 16 Killed in Nova Scotia Shooting, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. (UTC-3) on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\" /> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1|911]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.\n\nThen, at around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately 37 kilometres (23 mi) north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of Wentworth Valley, on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the RCMP to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was sighted in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 17 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer]] and operating a replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 16 in rural Canada|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later stated that this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly twelve hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside a gas station restaurant at the [[Irving Oil]] Big Stop in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /> The [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, and at least two other police use-of-force incidents.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather stated that there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said that he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n== Victims ==\nAt least 19 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them Constable Stevenson, a 23-year veteran of the police force. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims, who included an elementary school teacher and a nurse,<ref name=\"BBC-52346447\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Gunman kills at least 16 in rural Canada|date=20 April 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420075915/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52346447\" />\n\n== Perpetrator ==\nThe RCMP identified Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19th after he was pronounced dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=2020-04-19|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called Wortman's home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two police cruisers he bought near his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by authorities to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> However, neighbours said that Wortman struggled with alcoholism, and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/20/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=After Nova Scotia Shooting, Families Mourn as Police Seek a Motive|first=Iliana|last=Magra|date=April 20, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[Quebec City mosque shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:bc0:f84:30dd:d803:64a5:a337", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "Abia Warriors F.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|Association football club in Nigeria}}\n{{Infobox football club\n|  fullname = \n|  nickname = \n|  founded  = 2003\n|  ground   = [[Umuahia Township Stadium]]\n|  capacity = 5,000\n|  website  = http://abiawarriorsfc.com\n|  owner    = [[Abia State|Abia State Government]]\n|  chairman = Emeka Inyama<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/abia-warriors-fc-unveil-new-patrons |title=Abia Warriors FC unveil new patrons |access-date=2014-01-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201141551/http://www.futaa.com/football/article/abia-warriors-fc-unveil-new-patrons |archive-date=2014-02-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|  manager  = Willy Udube(interim)\n|  league   = [[Nigeria Professional Football League]]\n|  season   = [[2019 Nigeria Professional Football League|2019]]\n|  position = 5th Group B\n|  pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=\n|  leftarm1=FFFFFF|body1=FF0000|rightarm1=FFFFFF|shorts1=FF0000|socks1=FF0000\n|  pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=|pattern_ra2=\n|  leftarm2=FF0000|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FF0000|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF\n|image = Abia_Warriors_Logo.svg\n}}\n'''Abia Warriors Football Club''' is a [[Nigerian]] [[Association football|football]] club based in the city of [[Umuahia]], [[Abia state]].\n\nBetween 2005 and 2010 they played under the name \"Orji Uzor Kalu FC\" in honor of Abia governor [[Orji Uzor Kalu]] who helped the club with state sponsorship upon promotion to the professional level. They reverted to their old name in summer of 2010.<ref>[http://www.vanguardngr.com/2010/07/ouk-fc-reverts-to-abia-warriors/ OUK reverts to Abia Warriors]</ref>\n\nThey won promotion to the [[Nigeria Premier League]] for the first time in August 2013 after winning their division on the last day.<ref>[http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/home/131666-abia-warriors-fc-taraba-crown-join-giwa-in-glo-premier-league http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/home/131666-abia-warriors-fc-taraba-crown-join-giwa-in-glo-premier-league] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922232459/http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/home/131666-abia-warriors-fc-taraba-crown-join-giwa-in-glo-premier-league |date=September 22, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Current squad 2019/2020==\n{{fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Edwin Nwakanma]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Tambe Charles]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=33|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Uche Okafor]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=35|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Godgift Elkanah]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=3|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Ubong Williams]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Chinedu Ozor]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=6|nat=Cameroon|name=[[Jean-Parfait Ledoux]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=26|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Ebetomame Oghenetega]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=29|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Innocent Gabriel]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Samson P]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Emeka I]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Abdullahi Fatai]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Promise Ogu]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Keumian Guy]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Hammed Yakub]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Adekunle Adeleke]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Somtochukwu Omini]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=34|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Okemmiri Anthony]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Jimoh Oni]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Shedrack Asiegbu]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Auta Phillip]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Atilola Abdulsalam Tunde]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Odeh James]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Ikedinachi Nwakanma]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Emmanuel Ugwuka]]|pos=}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Obaroakpo A]]|pos=}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Paul Samson]]|pos=}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Ugochukwu Anozie]]|pos=}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Notable Players==\n*{{flagicon|Benin}} [[Raimi Kola]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100313213911/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/nig05.html 2005 Division 1 table]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Nigerian Premier League}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Abia State]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs in Nigeria]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-footyclub-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Association football club in Nigeria}}\n{{Infobox football club\n|  fullname = \n|  nickname = \n|  founded  = 2003\n|  ground   = [[Umuahia Township Stadium]]\n|  capacity = 5,000\n|  website  = http://abiawarriorsfc.com\n|  owner    = [[Abia State|Abia State Government]]\n|  chairman = Emeka Inyama<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/abia-warriors-fc-unveil-new-patrons |title=Abia Warriors FC unveil new patrons |access-date=2014-01-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201141551/http://www.futaa.com/football/article/abia-warriors-fc-unveil-new-patrons |archive-date=2014-02-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|  manager  = Willy Udube(interim)\n|  league   = [[Nigeria Professional Football League]]\n|  season   = [[2019 Nigeria Professional Football League|2019]]\n|  position = 5th Group B\n|  pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=\n|  leftarm1=FFFFFF|body1=FF0000|rightarm1=FFFFFF|shorts1=FF0000|socks1=FF0000\n|  pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=|pattern_ra2=\n|  leftarm2=FF0000|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FF0000|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF\n|image = Abia_Warriors_Logo.svg\n}}\n'''Abia Warriors Football Club''' is a [[Nigerian]] [[Association football|football]] club based in the city of [[Umuahia]], [[Abia state]].\n\nBetween 2005 and 2010 they played under the name \"Orji Uzor Kalu FC\" in honor of Abia governor [[Orji Uzor Kalu]] who helped the club with state sponsorship upon promotion to the professional level. They reverted to their old name in summer of 2010.<ref>[http://www.vanguardngr.com/2010/07/ouk-fc-reverts-to-abia-warriors/ OUK reverts to Abia Warriors]</ref>\n\nThey won promotion to the [[Nigeria Premier League]] for the first time in August 2013 after winning their division on the last day.<ref>[http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/home/131666-abia-warriors-fc-taraba-crown-join-giwa-in-glo-premier-league http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/home/131666-abia-warriors-fc-taraba-crown-join-giwa-in-glo-premier-league] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922232459/http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/home/131666-abia-warriors-fc-taraba-crown-join-giwa-in-glo-premier-league |date=September 22, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Current squad 2019/2020==\n{{fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Edwin Nwakanma]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Tambe Charles]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=33|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Uche Okafor]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=35|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Godgift Elkanah]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=3|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Ubong Williams]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Chinedu Ozor]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=6|nat=Cameroon|name=[[Jean-Parfait Ledoux]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=26|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Ebetomame Oghenetega]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=29|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Innocent Gabriel]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Samson P]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Emeka I]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Abdullahi Fatai]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Promise Ogu]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Keumian Guy]]|pos=MD}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Hammed Yakub]]|pos=MD}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Adekunle Adeleke]]|pos=MD}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Somtochukwu Omini]]|pos=MD}}\n{{Fs player|no=34|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Okemmiri Anthony]]|pos=MD}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Jimoh Oni]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Shedrack Asiegbu]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Auta Phillip]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Atilola Abdulsalam Tunde]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Odeh James]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Ikedinachi Nwakanma]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Emmanuel Ugwuka]]|pos=}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Obaroakpo A]]|pos=}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Paul Samson]]|pos=}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|nat=Nigeria|name=[[Ugochukwu Anozie]]|pos=}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Notable Players==\n*{{flagicon|Benin}} [[Raimi Kola]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100313213911/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/nig05.html 2005 Division 1 table]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Nigerian Premier League}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Abia State]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs in Nigeria]]\n\n\n{{Nigeria-footyclub-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ibagere", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurrent squad 2019/2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abia_Warriors_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Club Am\u00e9rica", "text_new": "{{About|the men's football club|the women's football club|Club Am\u00e9rica (women)|other uses}}\n{{short description|Mexican association football club}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Am\u00e9rica \n| image = Club Am\u00e9rica crest.svg\n| upright = .8\n| fullname = Club de F\u00fatbol Am\u00e9rica S.A. de C.V.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica|url=http://ligamx.net/cancha/club/1/america|publisher=LigaMX.net}}</ref>\n| short name = AME, CFA\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1916|10|12}}\n| nickname = ''Las \u00c1guilas'' (The Eagles)<ref>{{cite web|title=La historia de las \u00c1guilas del Am\u00e9rica\n|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/la-historia-de-las-aguilas-del-america|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|date=20 September 2019}}</ref><br>''Los Azul-Cremas'' (The Blue-Creams)<ref name=\"apodos\">{{cite web|title=Los \"apodos\" del Am\u00e9rica en sus 96 a\u00f1os|url=http://pulsoslp.com.mx/2012/10/12/los-apodos-del-america-en-sus-96-anos/|publisher=Pulso|accessdate=12 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430054302/http://pulsoslp.com.mx/2012/10/12/los-apodos-del-america-en-sus-96-anos/|archive-date=30 April 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br>''Los Millonetas'' (The Millionaires)<ref name=\"apodos\" />\n| ground = [[Estadio Azteca]]\n| capacity = 87,523<ref>{{cite web |url=http://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/united-2026-bid-book.pdf?cloudid=w3yjeu7dadt5erw26wmu |title=2026 FIFA World Cup Bid Book |format=PDF |page=161 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Grupo Televisa]]\n| chrtitle = Chairman\n| chairman = [[Emilio Azc\u00e1rraga Jean]]\n| mgrtitle = Manager\n| manager = [[Miguel Herrera]]\n| league = [[Liga MX]]\n| season = [[2019\u201320 Liga MX season#Torneo Apertura|Apertura 2019]]\n| position = 6th (Runners-up)\n| current = 2019\u201320 Club Am\u00e9rica season\n| pattern_la1 = _america1920h\n| pattern_b1 = _america1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _america1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = _america1920h\n| pattern_so1 = _america1920h\n| leftarm1 = _america1920h\n| body1 = _america1920h\n| rightarm1 = _america1920h\n| shorts1 = _america1920h\n| socks1 = FFFF94\n| pattern_la2 = _america1920a\n| pattern_b2 = _america1920a\n| pattern_ra2 = _america1920a\n| pattern_sh2 = _america1920a\n| pattern_so2 = _america1920a\n| leftarm2 = 000040\n| body2 = 000040\n| rightarm2 = 000040\n| shorts2 = 000040\n| socks2 = 000040\n| pattern_la3 = _america1920t\n| pattern_b3 = _america1920t\n| pattern_ra3 = _america1920t\n| pattern_sh3 = _america1920t\n| pattern_so3 = _america1920t\n| leftarm3 = _america1920t\n| body3 = _america1920t\n| rightarm3 = _america1920t\n| shorts3 = _america1920t\n| socks3 = 00d8e3\n| website = http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/\n}}\n'''Club de F\u00fatbol Am\u00e9rica S.A. de C.V.''', commonly known as '''Club Am\u00e9rica''' or simply '''Am\u00e9rica''', is a professional [[association football|football]] club based in [[Mexico City]], Mexico. Nicknamed ''Las \u00c1guilas'' (The Eagles), it competes in [[Liga MX]], the top tier of [[Mexican football league system|Mexican football]]. The club was founded in 1916, and since 1959 has been owned by media company [[Grupo Televisa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Grupo Televisa, S.A.B.|url=http://www.securities.com/Public/company-profile/MX/Grupo_Televisa_SAB_en_1223999.html|work=Internet Securities, Inc.|publisher=Euromoney Institutional Investor company|accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> The team plays its home games at the [[Estadio Azteca]], the largest stadium in Mexico and Latin America, and the [[List of association football stadiums by capacity|seventh largest]] association football-specific stadium in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://es.fifa.com/u17worldcup/news/newsid=1407679/index.html|title= El Azteca, cuna de campeones (The Azteca, home of champions)|publisher=[[FIFA]] |date= 29 March 2011|accessdate=2011-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 10 Largest Football Stadiums in the World|url=http://soccerlens.com/largest-football-stadiums/36427/|publisher=Soccerlens|accessdate=24 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top Ten Biggest Soccer Stadiums in the World|url=http://sportige.com/top-ten-soccer-stadiums/|publisher=Sportige|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe club has a long-standing rivalry with [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]], as both are the most successful and most popular clubs in the country, and are the only [[List of unrelegated association football clubs|clubs to have never been relegated]] to the [[Ascenso MX|second division]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Coventric!|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/coventric.html|website=RSSSF.com|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> Matches between them are known as ''[[El S\u00faper Cl\u00e1sico (Mexico)|El S\u00faper Cl\u00e1sico]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico's Cl\u00e1sico de Cl\u00e1sicos|url= https://www.fifa.com/news/y=2010/m=4/news=mexico-clasico-clasicos-1188625.html|publisher=FIFA.com|accessdate=1 April 2010}}</ref> considered to be the biggest rivalry in Mexico, and one of the biggest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=FourFourTwo's 50 Biggest Derbies in the World: 20-11|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/fourfourtwos-50-biggest-derbies-world-20-11?page=0%2C1|website=FourFourTwo|publisher=FourFourTwo|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mewis |first=Joe |title=The top 50 football derbies on the world 20-11: Italian and Brazilian rivalries plus 'the Mother of all Battles' |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/top-50-football-derbies-world-11313881 |publisher=Mirror |website=mirror.co.uk |accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Top 10 club rivalries in world soccer |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/photo/2017/04/21/top-rivalries-club-world-soccer |magazine=Sports Illustrated |accessdate= 21 April 2017}}</ref> Am\u00e9rica also play local derbies against [[Cruz Azul]] and [[Club Universidad Nacional]].\n\nThe club has won a record thirteen league titles, as well as a record six [[Copa M\u00e9xico]] titles, and six [[Campe\u00f3n de Campeones]] cups. In international competitions, Am\u00e9rica has won ten [[FIFA]] recognized club trophies, the most for a club from the [[CONCACAF]] region. It has won a record seven [[CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions Cup/Champions League]] titles, two [[Copa Interamericana]] cups and one [[CONCACAF Giants Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica: 100 years of Mexico's bad guys|url=https://www.fifa.com/news/y=2008/m=5/news=the-giants-who-opened-doors-772969.html|publisher=FIFA.com|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gorozpe|first=Carlos|title=Am\u00e9rica es el equipo de la Concacaf con m\u00e1s t\u00edtulos internacionales|url=http://www.record.com.mx/futbol-nacional/2011-10-12/america-es-el-equipo-de-la-concacaf-con-mas-titulos-internacionales|publisher=Diario R\u00e9cord|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"EU\" >{{cite news|last=D\u00e1valos|first=Juan Antonio|title=Am\u00e9rica, club mexicano con m\u00e1s t\u00edtulos internacionales|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/465619.html|newspaper=El Universal|accessdate=4 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Foundation===\nBy 1916 football was already a popular sport in Mexico, particularly amongst college students in Mexico City. College students from Colegio Mascarones and Colegio Marista de la Perpetua formed two football teams with the names R\u00e9cord and Col\u00f3n. On 12 October 1916, the two squads decided to consolidate to make a more competitive squad. Many names were considered for this new squad, and team player Pedro \"Cheto\" Quintanilla suggested the name \"Am\u00e9rica\", since they had formed the team on [[Columbus Day]] ''(D\u00eda del descubrimiento de Am\u00e9rica)''. The players agreed and soon designed a crest which had the map of the Americas centered with a 'C' for \"Club\" on the left and an 'A' for \"Am\u00e9rica\" on the right. The players had to decide on their team colours. [[Rafael Garza Guti\u00e9rrez]] went to get some of his father's navy blue trousers and a yellow shirt and it was decided amongst the group that those would be the club's colors.<ref name=\"Uniforme\">{{cite web|title=Primer uniforme del Club Am\u00e9rica.|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/el-primer-uniforme-del-club-america|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n\n[[File:America23dz7.jpg|thumb|250px|Am\u00e9rica squad 1924\u20131925]]\nIn 1916, Club Am\u00e9rica had to prove itself to the Mexican Football League, which consisted primarily of foreign-born players.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} At the time, Am\u00e9rica was the only club in Mexico City with Mexican-born players. [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]], [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]], [[Real Club Espa\u00f1a]], [[Germania FV|Germania]], and [[Asturias F.C.|Asturias]] were already members of the ''Liga Mayor de la Ciudad''. Am\u00e9rica's acceptance into the league rested on three games they had to win. Am\u00e9rica won two games, tied the third and were accepted.\n\nIn 1919, the team changed its name to Club Uni\u00f3n, though the club returned to the name Am\u00e9rica the following year.<ref name=\"1917-42\"/> From 1924 to 1928, Am\u00e9rica was crowned league champion and was able to attract impressive crowds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica campe\u00f3n 1925\u201326|url=http://clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=8407|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de Liga 1927\u201328|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-liga-1927-28|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013Sitio Oficial}}</ref> In 1926, Am\u00e9rica became the first Mexican club to play outside of Mexico.<ref name=\"1917-42\">[http://www.esmas.com/clubamerica/nuestroclub/historiaold/315615.html \"Inicia la aventura (1917\u20131942).\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050104015039/http://www.esmas.com/clubamerica/nuestroclub/historiaold/315615.html |date=4 January 2005 }} www.esmas.com. Redaccion. {{in lang|es}}</ref> Aside from broadening their horizons, Club Am\u00e9rica along with Atlante petitioned to reduce the number of foreign players in the league. Shortly after the [[Federaci\u00f3n Mexicana de F\u00fatbol Asociaci\u00f3n|Mexican Football Federation]] was formed in 1928, Rafael Garza Guti\u00e9rrez was designated as the head coach of the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]]. Most of the national team squad that participated in the [[Football at the 1928 Summer Olympics|1928 Summer Olympics]] and [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930 World Cup]] consisted of players from Club Am\u00e9rica.<ref>{{cite web|title=1931\u20131940|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/1931-1940|publisher=Club America&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n\n===1940\u20131969===\nUntil 1942, Mexico had several leagues, although the league in Mexico City was considered the most developed. In 1942\u201343, the first National League was established and it was known as the Liga Mayor (Major League). Club Am\u00e9rica had declined from its then-prime of the 1920s and 1930s: aging players, diminishing financial resources, and resulting lack of interest made the team a bottom-feeder at the start of the beginning stage of the professional era<sup>[[#7|7]]</sup>.\n\nIt was also during this time that the rivalry with [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]] was born; especially during the 1945\u20131946 season when Guadalajara beat Am\u00e9rica by 6\u20134 and 4\u20132 scorelines. The 1951\u20131952 season saw Am\u00e9rica finish in 11th place out of 12, with a 3-point-advantage over [[C.D. Veracruz|Veracruz]], who were relegated. In 1954 Am\u00e9rica defeated rivals Guadalajara on penalties after a 0\u20130 draw in the [[Copa M\u00e9xico]] final, thus winning their first league cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de Copa 1953\u201354|url=http://clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=8484|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, the club was sold to soft drink manufacturer [[Jarritos]]. The new owner was trying to build upon the club's National Cup titles in 1954 and 1955 against Guadalajara.<ref>{{cite web|title=Copa M\u00e9xico 1954\u20131955: Am\u00e9rica vs Chivas|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/copa-mexico-1954-1955-america-vs-chivas|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> During the 1954\u201355 season Am\u00e9rica won their first [[Campe\u00f3n de Campeones]] championship, defeating [[Zacatepec]] 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica campe\u00f3n de campeones 1954\u20131955|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-campeones-1954-1955|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> The owner failed to build upon previous success and on 22 July 1959, [[Emilio Azc\u00e1rraga Milmo]], owner of [[Telesistema Mexicano]], bought Am\u00e9rica from Isaac Bessudo.<ref>[http://www.esmas.com/clubamerica/nuestroclub/historiaold/315616.html \"Epoca profesional (1943\u20131969).\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041205140539/http://www.esmas.com/clubamerica/nuestroclub/historiaold/315616.html |date=5 December 2004 }} www.esmas.com. Redaccion. {{in lang|es}}</ref> Following the acquisition, Azc\u00e1rraga told his players, \"I do not know much about football, but I do know a lot about business, and this, gentlemen, will be a business.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Centenario Club Am\u00e9rica: El Tigre los salv\u00f3 \u2013 Cap\u00edtulo 4 |url=https://www.futboltotal.com.mx/2016/10/centenario-club-america-el-tigre-los-salvo/ |website=Futbol Total |accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 1959\u20131960 season saw Am\u00e9rica reach second place in the league, behind Guadalajara. On 21 April 1964, at the [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]], the team, now coached by [[Alejandro Scopelli]], defeated [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]] 6\u20135 in the final match of the [[Copa M\u00e9xico]]. During the match Alfonso Portugal scored five of Am\u00e9rica's six; Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez scored the other goal to win the championship.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de Copa temporada 1963\u20131964|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-copa-temporada-1963-1964|publisher=Club America&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May 1965, Am\u00e9rica regained the Mexican \"Copa\" championship after a 4\u20130 victory over [[Monarcas Morelia|Morelia]] at the [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario]]. The goals were scored by [[Javier Fragoso]] and [[Vav\u00e1]], each scoring twice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica derrot\u00f3 a Morelia en la final de la Copa M\u00e9xico 1964\u20131965|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-derroto-a-morelia-en-la-final-de-la-copa-mexico-1963-1964|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n\n===1970s===\nAfter Mexico hosted the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]], the league tournament format was changed in response to the championship's disputed winners,{{Clarify|dated-March 2015;need a very short description of controversy WITH citation(s)|date=March 2015}} hence the Liguilla (play-offs) format was started. The first play-off final was in 1971 between [[Club Toluca|Toluca]] and Am\u00e9rica, leaders of Groups 1 and 2, respectively. After a 0\u20130 draw in Toluca, Am\u00e9rica obtained their second league title after winning the second-leg 2\u20130 at the Estadio Azteca.<ref>{{cite web|title=Partidos memorables Am\u00e9rica vs Toluca|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/partidos-memorables-america-vs-toluca|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> The following season saw Am\u00e9rica eliminated from the playoffs by [[Cruz Azul]]. Am\u00e9rica would defeat Cruz Azul the 1973 Copa M\u00e9xico final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-copa-73-74|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de Copa 73\u201374|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficia}}</ref> A few years followed in which Am\u00e9rica did not qualify for the playoffs. They finished in first place during the 1975\u20131976 season, and defeated [[Tecos UAG]] and Union de Curtidores in the quarter-finals and semi-finals to reach the final against [[Club Universidad de Guadalajara|Universidad de Guadalajara]]. Am\u00e9rica won the championship after beating UDG in the [[Jalisco Stadium]] 3\u20130 and 1\u20130 at the Estadio Azteca.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica campe\u00f3n de Liga 1975\u201376|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=17862|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140911113217/http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=17862|archivedate=11 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They also won the Campe\u00f3n de Campeones title by beating [[Tigres UANL]] 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de Campeones 1975-1976|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/comunicados/america-campeon-de-campeones-1975-1976/|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica \u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1977 Copa Interamericana|1977]], Am\u00e9rica participated in their first [[Copa Interamericana]], playing against Argentine club [[Boca Juniors]], winners of the [[1977 Copa Libertadores]]. After losing the first-leg and winning the second, Am\u00e9rica would win the championship in a playoff match in 1978 by a score of 2\u20131 after extra-time, with a last second free-kick goal by midfielder [[Carlos Reinoso]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de la Copa Interamericana 1978|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-la-copa-interamericana-1978|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> Am\u00e9rica became the first team from Mexico and from the CONCACAF region to win the competition. Am\u00e9rica also became the first confederation side to earn the \"double\" in a single year as it won the delayed [[1977 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]].<ref name=CONCACAF>{{cite web|title=CONCACAF Retro: Club America wins first two international titles in 1978|url=http://www.concacaf.com/article/concacaf-retro-club-america-wins-first-two-international-titles-in-1978|access-date=17 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317021610/http://www.concacaf.com/article/concacaf-retro-club-america-wins-first-two-international-titles-in-1978|archive-date=17 March 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===1980s===\nThe 1980s are generally considered Am\u00e9rica's \"golden decade\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Calder\u00f3n|first=Carlos|title=El Am\u00e9rica de los ochenta|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/editoriales/carlos-calderon/2009/02/el-america-de-los-ochenta|publisher=Medio Tiempo|accessdate=22 February 2009}}</ref> During this period, Am\u00e9rica won the league title [[Mexican football champions#Liguilla (1970-1996)|five times]], including three consecutive titles; the 1983\u201384 season, the 1984\u201385 season,<ref>{{cite web|title=El primer bicampeonato americanista en la era profesional|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/el-primer-bicampeonato-americanista-de-la-era-profesional|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> the Prode-85 tournament, the 1987\u201388 and 1988\u201389 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=El segundo bicampeonato americanista en la era profesional|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/el-segundo-bicampeonato-americanista-en-la-era-profesional|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> They also won the Mexican Super Cup twice, in 1987\u201388 and 1988\u201389,<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica campe\u00f3n de campeones 87\u201388|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-campeones-en-la-87-88|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> as well as the [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup 1987|1987 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]].\n\nThe 1983\u20131984 season saw Am\u00e9rica reach the top of the table and reach the finals, where they would face arch-rivals [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]], who the previous season had eliminated Am\u00e9rica in the semi-finals. Following a 2\u20132 draw at the [[Estadio Jalisco]], Am\u00e9rica defeated Guadalajara in the Azteca Stadium 3\u20131, and a 5\u20133 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mart\u00ednez |first=Enrique| title=La Final del Siglo fue para el Am\u00e9rica |url=http://www.record.com.mx/futbol-futbol-nacional-america-chivas/la-final-del-siglo-fue-para-el-america |publisher=Diario R\u00e9cord |accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref> To date, it is the only match between these two teams in the league finals, though they would face each other in other phases of the playoffs. The series has since been dubbed the ''\"Final del Siglo\"'' (''\"Final of the Century\"'').<ref>{{cite web|title=El cl\u00e1sico m\u00e1s importante: Final del siglo Am\u00e9rica 3\u20131 Chivas 1983\u20131984|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/el-clasico-mas-importante-final-del-siglo-1984-america-3-1-chivas|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Las tres finales en que Am\u00e9rica y Chivas se han visto las caras |url=http://mexico.as.com/mexico/2015/09/24/futbol/1443047816_151919.html |newspaper=Diario AS |accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref> The following season Am\u00e9rica once again reached the finals, this time against city-rivals [[Pumas UNAM]]. After two draws in both the Azteca Stadium and the [[Estadio Ol\u00edmpico Universitario|Mexico '68 Stadium]], the last game was played in the [[Estadio Corregidora]] in [[Quer\u00e9taro]], where [[Daniel Brailovsky]] secured the championship for Am\u00e9rica by scoring two goals with the final score of 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|title=Club Am\u00e9rica vs Pumas&nbsp;\u2013 Gran Final 1985 Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/club-america-vs-pumas-gran-final-1985-america-campeon|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n\nDue to Mexico hosting the [[1986 World Cup]] and stadium and infrastructure preparations, the tournament was split in two short tournaments: Prode-85 and Mexico-86. Am\u00e9rica got the top of their group in the Prode-85 and defeated [[Leones Negros UdeG|Universidad de Guadalajara]] and Atlante to get to the final, where they played [[Jaibos Tampico Madero]]. The game in Tampico was a 4\u20131 victory for Tampico, but at the Azteca Stadium, Am\u00e9rica beat Tampico Madero 4\u20130 to win the championship.\n\nFor the 1987\u201388 season, Am\u00e9rica met UNAM in the final, in a replay of the 1985 final. They defeated UNAM by an aggregate score of 4\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica campe\u00f3n de Liga 87\u201388|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-liga-87-88|publisher=Club America&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> The following season, Am\u00e9rica once again reached the league final and faced Cruz Azul, which was the first time the two clubs met in the final since 1972. The first-leg finished in a 3\u20132 victory for Am\u00e9rica. A 2\u20132 draw in the second-leg meant Am\u00e9rica won the championship by a 5\u20134 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica cerr\u00f3 su \u00e9poca gloriosa de los 80s derrotando a Cruz Azul en la final de 1989|url=http://futbol.univision.com/article/1544237/2013-05-23/mexico/noticias/america-vs-cruz-azul-final-1989|publisher=[[Univision]]|accessdate=23 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714141518/http://futbol.univision.com/article/1544237/2013-05-23/mexico/noticias/america-vs-cruz-azul-final-1989|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nDuring the 1990s, Am\u00e9rica only managed to win the CONCACAF Champions' Cup in 1990,<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica campe\u00f3n del torneo de la CONCACAF 1990\u20131991|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-la-concacaf-1990-1991|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> a Copa Interamericana in 1993,<ref>{{cite web|title=Copa Interamericana&nbsp;\u2013 Historial|url=http://www.universofutbol.com.ar/plantillas/torneos/copainteramericana.php|publisher=Universo F\u00fatbol}}</ref> and a second CONCACAF Champions' Cup in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de CONCACAF 1992\u201393|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-concacaf-1992-93|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> During the 1990\u20131991 season, Am\u00e9rica dominated its group and reached the playoffs to eliminate Universidad de Guadalajara in the quarter-final round and Guadalajara in the semi-final round, only to reach the final and lose to UNAM.\n\nIn 1994, club president Emilio Diez Barroso announced the hiring of Dutch manager [[Leo Beenhakker]], who had previously coached Spanish club [[Real Madrid]] to a [[La Liga]] title. The club also announced the signing of two African players, [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon international]] [[Fran\u00e7ois Omam-Biyik]] and [[Zambia national football team|Zambian national team]] captain [[Kalusha Bwalya]]. Other Mexican players such as [[Joaqu\u00edn del Olmo]], [[Ra\u00fal Gutierrez]], among others were signed as well. Am\u00e9rica finished the season with 51 points, and scoring 88 goals. With only a few matches remaining in the regular season, Beenhakker was abruptly fired as manager. It was rumored that conflict between the coach and Diez Barosso regarding Beenhacker's defending of playing Del Olmo was the reason for his sacking.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leo Beenhakker revel\u00f3 por qu\u00e9 sali\u00f3 del Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/noticias/2010/03/16/leo-beenhakker-revelo-por-que-salio-del-america|publisher=Medio Tiempo|accessdate=16 March 2010}}</ref> Am\u00e9rica reached the semi-finals, losing to Cruz Azul. This Am\u00e9rica team is considered one of the best in the club's history, despite not winning any silverware.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leo Beenhakker no consigui\u00f3 hacer realidad el sue\u00f1o de sacar campe\u00f3n al Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.terra.com/deportes/articulo/html/fox68196.htm|publisher=T\u00e9rra Networks|accessdate= 24 November 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 Am\u00e9rica, along with Guadalajara, became the first Mexican club to participate in the [[Copa Libertadores]] tournament. They were inserted in a group where both teams confronted clubs from [[Venezuela]]. Am\u00e9rica finished in second position of the qualifying stage and advanced to the group stages. Am\u00e9rica was put in Group 3 along with Guadalajara and Brazilian clubs [[Gr\u00eamio]] and [[CR Vasco da Gama|Vasco da Gama]]. Am\u00e9rica qualified to the next round finishing in third place, being eliminated by Argentine club [[CA River Plate|River Plate]].<ref>{{cite web|title=M\u00e9xico y la Libertadores, 15 a\u00f1os de historia|url=http://deportes.publimetro.com.mx/fucho/mexico-y-la-libertadores-15-anos-de-historia|publisher=Publisport|accessdate=4 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130413152200/http://deportes.publimetro.com.mx/fucho/mexico-y-la-libertadores-15-anos-de-historia|archivedate=13 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\n[[File:Chonbuk clubamerica.jpg|thumb|300px|Am\u00e9rica in the [[2006 FIFA Club World Cup]] playing against [[Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors]] (South Korea)]]\n\nIn August 2001, Am\u00e9rica won the [[CONCACAF Giants Cup]] after defeating [[Major League Soccer|MLS]] club [[D.C. United]] 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|title=Club America Wins Giants Cup|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/aug/06/sports/sp-31192|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=6 August 2001}}</ref> The following year, Am\u00e9rica would reach the league final against [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]], winning by a 3\u20132 aggregate score. After losing in the first-leg 0\u20132, Am\u00e9rica won the second by the same scoreline, forcing extra-time to be played. A [[golden goal]] from a Hugo Norberto Castillo header in the 107th minute gave Am\u00e9rica the victory, and the club its first league championship in 13 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica campe\u00f3n Verano 2002|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-verano-2002|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n\nThe club once again reached the league final during the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2005|Clausura 2005]] tournament, finishing third in the standings and defeating [[Santos Laguna]] and [[Cruz Azul]] in the quarterfinals and semi-finals to face [[Tecos UAG]]. After a 1\u20131 draw in the first-leg, Am\u00e9rica was victorious in the second, winning the match 6\u20133 at the Estadio Azteca&nbsp;\u2013 7\u20134 on aggregate&nbsp;\u2013 to win the club's tenth league title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n del Clausura 2005|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-del-clausura-2005|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April 2006, Am\u00e9rica defeated fellow-Mexican side Toluca to win the [[2006 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], thus qualifying for the [[FIFA Club World Cup]] [[2006 FIFA Club World Cup|that same year]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de CONCACAF 2006|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-campeon-de-concacaf-2006|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref> At the tournament, Am\u00e9rica won its first match against [[Jeonbuk Hyundai Motors]] of South Korea. Am\u00e9rica went on to lose the next match against Spanish side [[FC Barcelona]]. It ended its participation in the tournament, losing the match for third place to [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] of Egypt.<ref>{{cite web|title=2006 FIFA Club World Cup&nbsp;\u2013 Overview|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/clubworldcup/japan2006/index.html|publisher=FIFA}}</ref>\n\n====2007====\nAfter the Club World Cup, Am\u00e9rica qualified for the playoffs of the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2007|Clausura 2007]] defeating Atlas and Guadalajara in the quarter and semi-finals. They played the final against [[CF Pachuca|Pachuca]], finishing runners-up.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pachuca, campe\u00f3n del futbol mexicano|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/427678.html|newspaper=El Universal|accessdate=27 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Apertura 2007|Apertura 2007]], after starting off the season on a poor run, [[Luis Fernando Tena]] was sacked,<ref>[http://www.orizabaenred.com.mx/cgi-bin/web?b=VERNOTICIA&%7Bnum%7D=56892: \"Se va Luis Fernando Tena del Am\u00e9rica\"]. Orizabaenred.com.mx. Retrieved October 7, 2007.</ref> and was replaced by [[Daniel Brailovsky]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Ruso\" Brailovsky es nuevo t\u00e9cnico del Am\u00e9rica de M\u00e9xico|url=http://wvw.nacion.com/ln_ee/2007/octubre/08/deportes1270152.html|publisher=nacion.com|accessdate=October 8, 2007}}</ref> After finishing third in their group and sixth in the general standings, Am\u00e9rica played [[Monarcas Morelia|Morelia]] for the last spot in the playoffs, being beaten 3\u20130 in the first-leg, and winning 1\u20130 in the second-leg. With this, Am\u00e9rica was eliminated from the competition.<ref>[http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/312118.monarcas-va-contra-santos.html: \"Morelia elimina a un grande\"]. ''[[El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2007.</ref>\n\nAm\u00e9rica also participated in the [[2007 Copa Sudamericana|Copa Sudamericana]], reaching the [[2007 Copa Sudamericana Finals|finals]] to play against [[Arsenal de Sarand\u00ed]] of Argentina. They would lose the first-leg at the [[Estadio Azteca]] by a 2\u20133 score, and win 2\u20131 in Argentina. The aggregate result was 4\u20134, but due to the [[away goals rule]], Arsenal won the championship.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arsenal, campe\u00f3n de la Sudamericana|url=http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/deportes/8-95789-2007-12-06.html|publisher=P\u00e1gina/12|accessdate=6 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nAm\u00e9rica finished 2007 ranked tenth in the [[IFFHS]]'s Club World Rankings, becoming the first Mexican club to reach the top ten.<ref>{{cite web|title=Club World Rankings 2007|url=http://iffhs.de/?eedbca388d85691a55685fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70a10e|publisher=International Football Federation of History and Statistics}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica, d\u00e9cimo mejor club del 2007: IFFHS|url=http://www.caracol.com.co/noticias/actualidad/america-decimo-mejor-club-del-2007-iffhs/20080108/nota/530586.aspx|publisher=Caracol|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525174959/http://www.caracol.com.co/noticias/actualidad/america-decimo-mejor-club-del-2007-iffhs/20080108/nota/530586.aspx|archivedate=25 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica, d\u00e9cimo en la clasificaci\u00f3n mundial de la IFFHS.|url=http://www.orizabaenred.com.mx/cgi-bin/web?b=VERNOTICIA&%7Bnum%7D=59212|publisher=orizabaenred.com.mx|accessdate=31 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n====2008====\nAm\u00e9rica started off 2008 winning the [[2008 InterLiga|InterLiga]] tournament, defeating [[Cruz Azul]] 5\u20133 on penalties in the [[InterLiga 2008 Final|final]] following a 3\u20133 draw after 120 minutes, thus assuring qualification to the Copa Libertadores tournament that same year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica gana la Interliga y va a la Libertadores|url=http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/deportes/america_gana_interliga_clasifica_copa_libertadores_aguilas_cruz_azul_1301_08_deportes.html|publisher=Adnmundo|website=adnmundo.com|accessdate=13 January 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118070045/http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/deportes/america_gana_interliga_clasifica_copa_libertadores_aguilas_cruz_azul_1301_08_deportes.html|archivedate=18 January 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2008|Clausura tournament]] saw Am\u00e9rica end in next-to-last place in the general standings. This had not been seen since the mid-1950s. In the first five months of 2008, Am\u00e9rica was showered with twelve defeats, two draws and three victories, which resulted in the third-straight tournament without qualifying for the playoffs. The manager at the time was [[Rub\u00e9n Omar Romano]], who was one of the least successful coaches in the club's history.<ref>{{cite news|last=D\u00e1valos|first=Juan Antonio|title=Los 10 datos para el olvido de Romano con Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/503363.html|newspaper=El Universal|accessdate=1 May 2008}}</ref> Coincidently, after being replaced by [[Juan Antonio Luna]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Davalos, Parra|first=Juan Antonio, Jos\u00e9 \u00c1ngel|title=Juan Antonio Luna es el nuevo t\u00e9cnico del Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/503343.html|newspaper=El Universal|accessdate=30 April 2008}}</ref> Am\u00e9rica got their third victory of the Clausura against [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]]. Despite their poor domestic form, Am\u00e9rica fared well in the [[2008 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]], defeating Brazilian side [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]] in the round-of-16 3\u20130 at the [[Est\u00e1dio do Maracan\u00e3]], overturning a 2\u20134 first-leg deficit, and advancing to the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Am\u00e9rica dio un maracanazo; 3\u20130 al Flamengo y avanz\u00f3|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2008/05/08/index.php?section=deportes&article=a50n1dep|newspaper=La Jornada|accessdate=7 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\nFor the [[2010\u201311 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico season|Apertura 2010]], Am\u00e9rica brought back former manager [[Manuel Lapuente]], who led the club to the league title in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manuel Lapuente es el nuevo t\u00e9cnico del Am\u00e9rica de M\u00e9xico|url=http://www.futbolred.com/otras-ligas/noticias/mayo18mayo25/manuel-lapuente-es-el-nuevo-tecnico-del-america-de-mexico-/7724751|publisher=FutbolRed|accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref> The return of striker [[Vicente Mat\u00edas Vuoso]] and the signing of Uruguayan [[Vicente S\u00e1nchez]] gave Am\u00e9rica one of the most dangerous front lines in all of the league.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mat\u00edas Vuoso regresa al Am\u00e9rica|url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/deportes/2010/05/27/matias-vuoso-regresa-america|newspaper=El Economista|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=America Bring Vicente Sanchez Back To Mexico|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/114/mexico/2010/07/07/2014162/america-bring-vicente-sanchez-back-to-mexico|publisher=Goal.com|accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref> They finished the tournament in first place of Group 2, fourth in the general standings, with 27 points. With this, they would advance to the playoffs, and automatically qualify for the first time since 2008, for the [[2011 Copa Libertadores]]. They would be eliminated in the semi-finals by [[Santos Laguna]] by a 4\u20135 aggragate score.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ca\u00f1ada|first=Iv\u00e1n|title=Santos elimina al Am\u00e9rica y est\u00e1 en la Final|url=http://www.record.com.mx/node/36809|publisher=R\u00e9cord|accessdate=28 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130612112112/http://www.record.com.mx/node/36809|archivedate=12 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAm\u00e9rica had a bad start to the [[2010\u201311 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico season|Clausura 2011]] tournament; a 0\u20132\u20131 record in the first three games the tournament led to the sacking of Lapuente.<ref>{{cite web|title=Club America Fire Manager Manuel Lapuente|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2011/1/25/1956587/club-america-fire-manager-manuel-lapuente|publisher=SBNation|accessdate=25 January 2011}}</ref> Carlos Reinoso was named his successor,<ref>{{cite web|title=America sack Lapuente, bring Reinoso|url=http://m.goal.com/en-us/news/article?contentId=2323656&SID=oe0qhs3iicu573lq3qv53cimh6|archive-url=https://archive.is/20110711102802/http://m.goal.com/en-us/news/article?contentId=2323656&SID=oe0qhs3iicu573lq3qv53cimh6|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-07-11|publisher=Goal}}</ref> who had already managed the club two times before. His first game was against [[Club Atlas|Atlas]], which Am\u00e9rica won 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carlos Reinoso debuta y gana: Am\u00e9rica vence 2\u20130 a Atlas|url=http://www.publimetro.com.mx/deportes/carlos-reinoso-debuta-y-gana-america-vence-0-2-a-atlas/mkaD!Bvpew3RZJXq5o/|publisher=Publimetro|accessdate=30 January 2011}}</ref> Am\u00e9rica ended the Clausura with an 8\u20131\u20135 record, and would be eliminated in the quarter-finals by [[Monarcas Morelia|Morelia]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McCauley|first=Kevin|title=Monarcas Morelia Vs. Club America, 2011 Liguilla: 3\u20132 Full Time, Super Eagles Out|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2011/5/9/2161465/monarcas-morelia-vs-club-america-2011-liguilla-3-2-full-time-super|publisher=SBNation|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> On 18 September 2011, Reinoso was sacked as manager,<ref>[http://televisadeportes.esmas.com/futbol/futbolmexico/equipos/america/335134/queda-reinoso-fuera-del-america: \"Queda Reinoso fuera del Am\u00e9rica\"]. ''Televisa Deportes''. Retrieved 18 September 2011.</ref> with [[Alfredo Tena]] taking over as interim-manager. Am\u00e9rica would finish the [[2011\u201312 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico season|Apertura]] in 17th place, the second worse finish in the club's history. On 8 November, Michel Bauer stepped down as President.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michel Bauer qued\u00f3 fuera del Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2011/11/08/deportes/a43n2dep|newspaper=La Jornada|accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref> That same day, former Am\u00e9rica player [[Ricardo Pel\u00e1ez]] was presented as Sporting President, while Yon De Luisa would be named Operations President.<ref>[http://www.record.com.mx/galeria/futbol-nacional/ricardo-pelaez-nuevo-presidente-del-america: \"Ricardo Pel\u00e1ez, nuevo Presidente Deportivo del Am\u00e9rica\"]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Diario R\u00e9cord. Retrieved 11 November 2012.</ref> [[Miguel Herrera]] was presented as the club's new manager, the fourth in a year.<ref>[http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/news/story?id=1418139&s=mex&type=story: \"Miguel Herrera es el t\u00e9cnico del Am\u00e9rica\"]. ''ESPN Deportes''. Retrieved 16 November 2011.</ref> In his first year at the helm, Herrera brought the team to the semi-finals on two consecutive occasions.\n\nOn 26 May 2013, Am\u00e9rica won their [[2012\u201313 Liga MX season#Torneo Clausura|eleventh league title]] by defeating Cruz Azul in the [[2013 Liga MX Clausura Liguilla#Final|Clausura final]] 4\u20132 on penalties after a dramatic comeback from a 0\u20131 first-leg loss to win 2\u20131 in the second-leg, and tie 2\u20132 on aggregate, with goalkeeper [[Mois\u00e9s Mu\u00f1oz]] scoring the second goal in injury-time.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00a1Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n de la Liga MX!|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-es-campeon-de-la-liga-mx|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=May 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Vertelney|first=Seth|title=America win Liga MX Clausura title|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/108345/america-vs-cruz-azul/report:|publisher=Goal|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ter\u00e1n|first=Juan Manuel|title=\u00a1Am\u00e9rica, Campe\u00f3n del Clausura 2013!|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2013/05/26/america-campeon-del-clausura-2013_46948|publisher=Medio Tiempo|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mulroy|first=Peter J.|date=26 May 2013|title=America Vs. Cruz Azul: Second Leg of 2013 Mexican Clausura Championship Ends With Shootout As America Outlasts Cruz In Epic Finale; Recap|url=http://www.latintimes.com/america-vs-cruz-azul-second-leg-2013-mexican-clausura-championship-ends-shootout-america-outlasts|work=Latin Times|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica es campe\u00f3n del Torneo Clausura 2013 de LigaMX|url=http://noticierostelevisa.esmas.com/especiales/600486/america-campeon-del-torneo-clausura-2013-ligamx/|publisher=Noticiero Televisa|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref> With this, Am\u00e9rica tied Guadalajara for most league titles.<ref>{{cite web|last=Marshall|first=Tom|title=America title a reminder that Chivas have much to do|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/guadalajara/219/blog/post/1843536/america-win-ups-pressure-on-chivas-response|publisher=[[ESPN FC]]|accessdate=May 28, 2013}}</ref> For the [[2013\u201314 Liga MX season#Torneo Apertura|Apertura 2013]], Am\u00e9rica finished the regular phase of the tournament at the top of the standings with 37 points and would again appear in the league final, though failing to achieve a repeat, being defeated by [[Club Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]] by an aggregate score of 1\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCarthy|first=Kyle|title=Club Leon win sixth Primera title|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/foxsoccer/mexico/story/club-america-1-3-leon-estadio-azteca-second-leg-match-report-121513|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> On 17 December 2013, [[Antonio Mohamed]] was announced as Am\u00e9rica's new manager for the [[2013\u201314 Liga MX season#Clausura|Clausura 2014]] tournament, replacing Miguel Herrera after two years in charge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mohamed presentado como nuevo t\u00e9cnico americanista|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/mohammed-presentado-como-nuevo-tecnico-americanista|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=December 17, 2013}}</ref> Am\u00e9rica would finish fifth in the standings, and was eliminated in the quarter-finals by Santos Laguna due to the away-goals rule after drawing 6\u20136 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ruiz|first=Alberto|date=3 May 2014|title=Santos complet\u00f3 el milagro y va a Semis|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/cronicas/2014/05/03/santos-completo-el-milagro-y-va-a-semis_53435|publisher=Medio Tiempo|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAm\u00e9rica finished the [[2014\u201315 Liga MX season#Apertura|Apertura 2014]] tournament at the top of the general standings with 31 points, and defeated [[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]] and [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]] in the quarter-finals and semi-finals, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=El camino del campe\u00f3n: Am\u00e9rica|url=http://laaficion.milenio.com/america/America-campeon-Mohamed-Tigres-Final-Liguilla-Estadio_Azteca_0_427157436.html|publisher=La Afici\u00f3n|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref> Prior to the league final, the club was marred with controversy, such as media speculation regarding the future of Antonio Mohamed (he ultimately admitted he would leave the club after the final), and the separation of [[Paul Aguilar]] from the team before playing the first-leg of the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=America coach Mohamed separates Aguilar from squad|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/114/mexico/2014/12/06/6838182/america-coach-mohamed-separates-aguilar-from-squad|publisher=Goal|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> On 14 December, Am\u00e9rica won a record-twelfth league title after defeating [[Tigres UANL]] 3\u20131 on aggregate in the final, coming back from a 0\u20131 first-leg loss to win 3\u20130 in the second-leg at the Estadio Azteca.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cronica: Am\u00e9rica Campe\u00f3n|url=http://clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=20346|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=14 December 2014}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Am\u00e9rica vence 3\u20131 a Tigres y obtiene el d\u00e9cimosegundo t\u00edtulo|url=http://www.espndeportes.com/futbol/cronica?id=410238|publisher=ESPN Deportes|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Am\u00e9rica conquista la liga de M\u00e9xico tras derrotar a Tigres|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2014/12/15/internacional/1418626373_769566.html|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Club America captures Liga MX crown with conquest of Tigres|url=http://prosoccertalk.nbcsports.com/2014/12/15/club-america-captures-la-liga-mx-crown-with-conquest-of-tigres/|publisher=NBC Sports|date=15 December 2014|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> Three days after winning the final, Am\u00e9rica announced [[Gustavo Matosas]] as Mohamed's successor, signing a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gustavo Matosas es el nuevo D.T. \u00c1guila|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=20499|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=17 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141217194900/http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=20499|archivedate=17 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, the club won its sixth [[2014\u201315 CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions League]] title after defeating [[Montreal Impact]] in the [[2015 CONCACAF Champions League Finals|finals]] by a 5\u20133 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite news|last=Logotheti|first=Paul|date=29 April 2015|title=Club America beats Montreal Impact, claims CONCACAF Champions League title|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mls/2015/04/29/club-america-montreal-impact-concacaf-champions-league-title/26618651/|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref> Despite an inconsistent campaign throughout the [[2014\u201315 Liga MX season#Torneo Clausura|Clausura]] tournament, Am\u00e9rica managed to finish second in the standings, though was eliminated by [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]] in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica eliminado por el Pachuca|url=http://diario.mx/Deportes/2015-05-16_d1b6365d/america-eliminado-por-el-pachuca/|publisher=El Diario|accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref> Three days later, with various media reports suggesting Gustavo Matosas would be sacked due to differences with the board regarding player acquisitions and departures,<ref>{{cite web|last=Ca\u00f1ada|first=Iv\u00e1n|date=18 May 2015|title=Relaci\u00f3n entre Gustavo Matosas y Am\u00e9rica pende de un hilo|url=http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/2376667/relacion-entre-gustavo-matosas-y-america-pende-de-un-hilo|publisher=ESPN Deportes|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref> it was confirmed in a press conference which was attended by both Matosas and club president Ricardo Pela\u00e9z that he would indeed leave after only six months in charge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matosas, fuera del Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/noticias/2015/05/19/matosas-fuera-del-america|publisher=Medio Tiempo|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref> On 26 May, [[Ignacio Ambr\u00edz]] was presented as the new manager, signing a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ignacio Ambriz presentado como nuevo t\u00e9cnico del Club Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=23344|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=26 May 2015}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Am\u00e9rica lost its [[2015 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]] quarter-final match to Chinese team [[Guangzhou Evergrande]], and defeated African club [[TP Mazembe]] to claim fifth place in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|title=Club Am\u00e9rica claim fifth place|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=275788/match=300338753/match-report.html|publisher=FIFA.com|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Am\u00e9rica successfully defended the CONCACAF Champions League title after defeating Tigres UANL 4\u20131 on aggregate in the [[2016 CONCACAF Champions League Finals|finals]], and winning a record seventh continental title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cronica: Am\u00e9rica 2-1 Tigres|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/comunicados/cronica-america-2-1-tigres/|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica \u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref> Am\u00e9rica had a strong final stretch towards the end of 2016, culminating with a 4th-place finish at the [[2016 FIFA Club World Cup|Club World Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica es cuarto lugar en el Mundial de Clubes |url=http://laaficion.milenio.com/america/mundial_de_clubes-club_america-tercer_lugar-atletico_nacional-fifa-milenio-la_aficion_0_867513458.html |work=La Afici\u00f3n |publisher=Grupo Milenio |accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> and finishing runners-up in the [[2016\u201317 Liga MX season|Apertura]] championship match against Tigres UANL.<ref>{{cite web|title=En ag\u00f3nico partido, Tigres vence a Am\u00e9rica en penales |url=http://www.espn.com.mx/futbol/cronica?juegoId=468819 |publisher=ESPN Deportes |accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nAm\u00e9rica won its record thirteenth league title following a 2\u20130 aggregate victory over [[Cruz Azul]] in the [[2018\u201319 Liga MX season#Torneo Apertura|2018 Apertura final]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Tolmich |first=Ryan |title=Club America top Cruz Azul to claim Liga MX Apertura crown |url=https://www.goal.com/en-ae/news/club-america-top-cruz-azul-to-claim-liga-mx-apertura-crown/pub01vbb9zug19adeimqlckni |website=Goal.com |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> In April 2019, Am\u00e9rica defeated [[Ascenso MX]] side [[FC Ju\u00e1rez]] in the final of the [[Clausura 2019 Copa MX|Clausura edition]] of the [[Copa MX]], winning a record sixth title.<ref>{{cite news|title=Am\u00e9rica es campe\u00f3n de Copa MX tras vencer a FC Ju\u00e1rez |url=https://www.milenio.com/futbol/club-america/america-campeon-copa-mx-vencer-fc-juarez |newspaper=Milenio |accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> In winning the cup, Am\u00e9rica also become the outright record holders of the Liga MX, Copa MX, and CONCACAF Champions League.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica se convierte en m\u00e1ximo ganador de copa; ya lo era de liga y Concacaf |url=http://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mexico/nota/_/id/5489866/america-se-convierte-en-maximo-ganador-de-copa-ya-lo-era-de-liga-y-concacaf |publisher=ESPN Deportes |language=Spanish |accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Crest and colors ==\n{{Commons|Club Am\u00e9rica kits}}\n[[File:Club Am\u00e9rica Retro.png|thumb|upright|100xp|Club Am\u00e9rica crest introduced in the 1920s. An updated version was introduced in 2016 and worn as part of the club's centenary.]]\nWhen Club Am\u00e9rica was founded in 1916, the crest consisted of the letter 'C', standing for \"Club\", overlapped by an 'A', which stood for \"Am\u00e9rica\".<ref>{{cite web|title=El primer escudo del Club Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/el-primer-escudo-del-club-america|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref> After a brief period in which the team's name was changed to Club Uni\u00f3n, it was reverted to Club Am\u00e9rica in the mid-1920s, and the crest was modified, with a map of the Americas behind the 'CA', and encased in a football, all in the team's colors&nbsp;\u2013 which were cream and blue.<ref name=\"publimetro\">{{cite web|title=La evoluci\u00f3n del escudo del Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.publimetro.com.mx/publisport/la-evolucion-del-escudo-del-america/ckVmjl!c89ofBESHnS7AjHsKuy8ig/|publisher=Publimetro|accessdate=12 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=El segundo y m\u00e1s emblem\u00e1tico escudo del Club Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/el-segundo-escudo-del-club-america|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=20 March 2013}}</ref> Since then, the badge has seen minimal change, such as the removal of a line at the crest's center at the beginning of the 21st century. During the early 1980s, the crest was surrounded by an image of an eagle (due to the club's nickname), and was even enclosed in a triangle.<ref name=\"publimetro\" />\n\nThe most recent modification of the crest was in 2010, with the yellow and blue more vibrant and a darker outline and border.<ref>{{cite web|title=El actual escudo del Club Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/el-actual-escudo-del-club-america|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nClub founder [[Rafael Garza Guti\u00e9rrez]] chose what would be Am\u00e9rica's first uniform. He took some of his father's navy blue trousers and a yellow-cream shirt and it was decided amongst the other players that those would be the club's colors.<ref name=\"Uniforme\" /> It would not be until the 1980s that the colors changed, with the cream replaced with a more solid yellow. Am\u00e9rica also played with a white shirt, but it was not as common.\n\nDuring the [[2011\u201312 Club Am\u00e9rica season#Torneo Apertura|Apertura 2011]] tournament&nbsp;\u2013 what would be the club's 95th anniversary&nbsp;\u2013 a commemorative jersey was unveiled paying homage to the original uniform, as well as an altered crest. The uniform was used during the league match against [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Am\u00e9rica lanza uniforme conmemorativo|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com//futbol/mexico/noticias/2011/10/07/america-lanza-uniforme-conmemorativo|website=Medio Tiempo|accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, as part of the club's centenary, a dark red away kit was revealed honouring Italian club [[Torino F.C.|Torino]], who functioned as the club's first opponent at the [[Estadio Azteca]] in the 1966 inaugural match.<ref>{{cite web|title=El nuevo jersey Club Am\u00e9rica 2016|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/comunicados/el-nuevo-jersey-club-america-2016/|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica \u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Stunning Club America 2016 Centenary Kits Revealed|url=http://www.footyheadlines.com/2016/03/club-america-2016-centenary-kit.html?m=1|website=Footy Headlines|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Kit suppliers and shirt sponsors ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left\"\n|-\n! Period\n! Kit supplier\n! Shirt sponsor\n|-\n|1984\u20131988\n|rowspan=3| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Adidas]]\n|| None\n|-\n|1988\u20131990\n|| {{flagicon|MEX}} [[BBVA Bancomer|Bancomer]]\n|-\n|1990\u20131993\n|rowspan=4| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Coca-Cola]]\n|-\n|1993\u20131994\n|| {{flagicon|BRI}} [[Umbro]]\n|-\n|1994\u20132000\n|| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Adidas]]\n|-\n|2000\u20132005\n|rowspan=4| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Nike, Inc|Nike]]\n|-\n|2005\u20132015\n|| {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Grupo Bimbo|Bimbo]]\n|-\n|2015\u20132018 \n|| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Huawei]]\n|-\n|2018\u2013 \n|| {{flagicon|USA}} [[AT&T]]\n|}\n\n== Nicknames ==\nThe football club has often had many nicknames throughout its history, some used by the club and others given for different reasons. These are some of them:\n\n\u2022 '''The Students''': This was a nickname that wasn't well known and only used in the early years of the club. When the team was first founded, this nickname was used by their rivals because the team was developed from the combination of two colleges: Mascarones and La Perpetua.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/historia/|title=Historia * Club Am\u00e9rica - Sitio Oficial|work=Club Am\u00e9rica - Sitio Oficial|access-date=2017-03-07|language=es-ES}}</ref> Because many of their [[Football player|players]] were college students, when Club America joined La Liga [[Liga MX|Mexicana]] (the Mexican Soccer League), it was composed mostly of young players.\n\n\u2022 '''The Blue-Creams or Creams''': This nickname was one of the more distinctive and oldest nicknames. Used since 1920, it is the reason the club used the colorways it did. Back then, the jerseys were a cream color while the shorts and socks were blue.\n\n\u2022 '''[[Atlantic canary|Canaries]]''': This was one of the nicknames they have been known as since the 1940s. This was given to them because of the yellow found in the uniform.\n\n\u2022 '''Millionaires''': This is a derogatory reference or version of the word millionaire. It started when businessman [[Emilio Azc\u00e1rraga Milmo|Emilio Azcarraga Milmo]] bought the team in 1959.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/news/y=2008/m=5/news=the-giants-who-opened-doors-772969.html|title=America, 100 years of Mexico's bad guys|last=FIFA.com|date=2008-05-21|work=FIFA.com|access-date=2017-03-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> Azcarraga hired the successful president of the [[Zacatepec|Club Zacatepec]], [[Guillermo Ca\u00f1edo de la B\u00e1rcena]], and started to hire other notable foreigner figures, focusing on money, to form a powerful team.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Football in the Americas : f\u00fatbol, futebol, soccer|last=Liz|first=Crolley|last2=M.|first2=Miller, Rory|date=2007-01-01|publisher=Institute for the Study of the Americas|isbn=9781900039802|oclc=473907754|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/footballinameric0000unse}}</ref>\n\n\u2022 '''[[Eagle]]s''': Although this emblem of the eagle had appeared briefly in one version of the club shield in the 1940s, it wasn't a popular nickname until the arrival of new club America President Emilio D\u00edez Barroso in the early 1980s. With the club looking for a new image, they wanted to have a representation of an animal that would show pride and domination of its environment. Supported by a strong campaign, they chose the eagles. This nickname remains popular to this day.\n\n== Grounds ==\n{{Main|Estadio Azteca}}\n{{See also|Instalaciones Club Am\u00e9rica en Coapa}}\n[[File:Panorama Estadio Azteca football game Club America.jpg|center|thumb|900px|A panorama of the Estadio Azteca during a league match against Tecos]]\n\nAm\u00e9rica plays its home games at the [[Estadio Azteca]] in Mexico City. The stadium was designed by Mexican architect [[Pedro Ram\u00edrez V\u00e1zquez]], and was inaugurated on 29 May 1966 with a match between Am\u00e9rica and [[FC Torino|Torino]], which was tied 2\u20132. The first goal was scored was by Brazilian Arlindo Dos Santos and the second by [[Jos\u00e9 Alves]].<ref>{{cite web|title=El Azteca|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/club-america/el-estadio-azteca/el-azteca|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140215142141/http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/club-america/el-estadio-azteca/el-azteca|archivedate=15 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Gustavo D\u00edaz Ordaz]], President of Mexico, made the initial kick and [[Sir Stanley Rous]], [[FIFA]] President, was the witness.\n\nThe club has shared the stadium as a home ground with the [[Mexico national football team]] since its inauguration. Other club sides have also used the stadium as their home at different times, namely [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]] (1966\u201370 and 1982\u20132003), [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]] (1966\u201382, 1996\u20132001 and 2004\u20132007), [[Club Universidad Nacional|Universidad Nacional]] (1967\u20131969), [[Atl\u00e9tico Espa\u00f1ol]] (1970\u20131982) and [[Cruz Azul]] (1971\u20131996).\n\nAs well as acting as a home ground the stadium has also hosted the [[1968 Summer Olympics]], [[1970 FIFA World Cup]], [[1975 Pan American Games]], [[1983 FIFA World Youth Championship]], [[1986 FIFA World Cup]], [[1999 FIFA Confederations Cup]], [[2011 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] Final, [[Copa Interamericana]], [[Copa Libertadores de Am\u00e9rica]], music concerts, political events and the visit of Pope [[John Paul II]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pide Juan Pablo II \"superar\" deficiencias en el progreso social|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/1999/01/26/llama.html|accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==Rivalries==\n\n===''El Super Cl\u00e1sico''===\n{{Main|El S\u00faper Cl\u00e1sico (Mexico)}}\n\n===''Cl\u00e1sico Capitalino''===\n{{Main|Cl\u00e1sico Capitalino}}\nThe rivalry between Club Am\u00e9rica and [[Club Universidad Nacional]] is known as the ''\"[[Cl\u00e1sico Capitalino]]''\",<ref name=\"GR\">{{cite web |publisher = Grupo Reforma |year = 2007 |url = http://foro.univision.com/univision/board/message?board.id=hinchas_futbol&message.id=270350#M270350 |work = Univision.com |title = Encuesta completa sobre el equipo m\u00e1s popular de M\u00e9xico |accessdate = 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071012171934/http://foro.univision.com/univision/board/message?board.id=hinchas_futbol&message.id=270350#M270350 |archivedate = 12 October 2007 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> due to the fact that both teams are based in [[Mexico City]]\u2014the country's capital. The first match between the two clubs took place on 1 July 1962, where Am\u00e9rica hosted UNAM, who had recently been promoted from the second division. In Mexico the match is often perceived as the representation of a struggle between two antagonistic powers and institutions: Club Am\u00e9rica is regarded as the club representing the establishment and the wealthy. The fact that the club is owned by the mass media company [[Televisa]] has further intensified this image. Club Universidad, representing the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico|Universidad Nacional Aut\u00f3noma de M\u00e9xico]], identifies itself as the club of the intellectuals and middle-class.<ref>{{cite web|title=FIFA Classic Rivalries: CF Am\u00e9rica VS Pumas UNAM&nbsp;\u2013 Mexico City's grudge game|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/rivalries/newsid=1333144/index.html|publisher=FIFA.com}}</ref> The rivalry is particularly fierce from UNAM's side: according to surveys the majority of their supporters consider Am\u00e9rica as their main rival. However, America's fans see it as an important match but deem the match against Chivas as more important.<ref name=\"Pumas vs. Am\u00e9rica\">{{cite web |author = Eduardo Hern\u00e1ndez Castro |year = 2003 |url = http://eleconomista.com.mx/deportes/2013/04/18/pumas-vida-america-no-lo-todo |title = Para Pumas la vida; para Am\u00e9rica, no lo es todo |work = El Economista |accessdate = 21 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===''Cl\u00e1sico Joven''===\n{{Main|Cl\u00e1sico Joven}}\nClub Am\u00e9rica's other capital-based rival is [[Cruz Azul]], with whom they compete in the derby known as the \"''[[Cl\u00e1sico Joven]]''\" (''Juvenile Classic'' in Spanish).<ref name=\"GR\"/> Although both teams reside in [[Mexico City]], Cruz Azul originated in Jasso, [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]]. In a similar perspective between Am\u00e9rica and UNAM's rivalry, the rivalry between Am\u00e9rica and Cruz Azul is also seen as based on social class differences: Am\u00e9rica representing the wealthy and powerful while Cruz Azul is said to represent the working class,<ref name=\"Archibold\">{{cite news|author=Archibold, Randal C.|date=25 October 2013|title=Mexican Writer Mines the Soccer Field for Metaphors|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/26/world/americas/mexican-writer-mines-the-soccer-field-for-metaphors.html?_r=0:|quote=With Cruz Azul and Am\u00e9rica taking to the field on the television behind him at the cantina, Mr. Villoro sought to put the game, a traditional matchup between dominant teams in the capital, in context.  \"This is the Mexico City classic,\" he explained. \"The game itself is one thing, who scores, who wins. But Cruz Azul represents the working class here; that is their following. Am\u00e9rica is the upper class, the rich or wannabe rich. So this condenses into the workers versus the wannabes.\"|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=26 October 2013}}</ref> hence fans of Cruz Azul and the team itself being dubiously referred to by the nickname of \"''Los Alba\u00f1iles''\" (''[[bricklayer]]s'' in Spanish), a reference to Cruz Azul's [[Cooperativa La Cruz Azul S.C.L.|eponymous parent company]], which is one of Mexico's major companies specializing in concrete and construction.\n\n==Support==\n[[File:Afici\u00f3n del Estadio azteca final 2019.jpg|thumb|upright|250xp|Am\u00e9rica supporters at Estadio Azteca]]\nEver since Am\u00e9rica was bought by [[Emilio Azc\u00e1rraga Milmo]] from Issac Bessudo in 1959, the club has had the unique distinction of being both one of the most popular clubs in Mexico, as well as the most hated.<ref>Garc\u00eda, Miguel \u00c1ngel.[http://www.laciudaddeportiva.com/odiame-cuando-quieras: \"\u00d3diame cuando quieras\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116121928/http://www.laciudaddeportiva.com/odiame-cuando-quieras: |date=16 January 2014 }}. La Cuidad Deportiva. Retrieved May 28, 2013.</ref> An emphasis on heavy spending on Mexican and foreign players and managers in subsequent seasons, as well as success in domestic and international competitions, created an increasing sense of enmity from rival fans. The fact that Azc\u00e1rraga Milmo was also the owner of telecommunications company [[Telesistema Mexicano]] furthered the notion that Am\u00e9rica was the club of the \"establishment\" and the \"wealthy\", while others were considered teams representing the \"working class\".<ref name=\"Archibold\" />\n\nIn December 2013 Mexican newspaper [[Reforma]] had Am\u00e9rica as the country's most popular club with 25 percent in a nationwide survey, and the most popular club in Mexico City. They were also voted the most hated club in the same survey with 41 percent of the votes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica el equipo m\u00e1s popular de M\u00e9xico|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/america-es-el-equipo-mas-popular-de-mexico-2|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013Sitio Oficial|accessdate= December 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Son favoritos Am\u00e9rica y L\u00e9on|url=http://gruporeforma-blogs.com/encuestas/?cat=43|publisher=Encuestas Grupo Reforma|accessdate=January 3, 2014}}</ref> According to a February 2015 poll conducted by Mexican pollster ''Consulta Mitofsky'', Am\u00e9rica is Mexico's most popular football club with 31.1 percent, and the most hated with 41.5 percent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica, el equipo m\u00e1s popular de M\u00e9xico|url=http://www.record.com.mx/articulo/noticias/3211411/futbol+futbol-nacional+america/america-el-equipo-mas-popular-de-mexico|publisher=Diario R\u00e9cord|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Am\u00e9rica tiene m\u00e1s seguidores que Chivas y Cruz Azul juntos|url=http://www.economiahoy.mx/futbol-eAm-mx/noticias/6465320/02/15/America-tiene-mas-seguidores-de-que-Chivas-y-Cruz-Azul-juntos.html#Kku80IvVX4VIAsiC|publisher=Econom\u00edaHoy|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=El m\u00e1s popular de M\u00e9xico|url=http://clubamerica.com.mx/single.php?id=21289|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|accessdate=10 February 2015}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> According to a study conducted by consulting agency EuroAmericas Sports Marketing, Am\u00e9rica is the most popular Mexican club in Asia, and the third most popular from the Americas after [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]] of Brazil and [[Boca Juniors]] of Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|last=Price|first=Daniel|date=20 November 2014|title=Club America, Corinthians and Boca Juniors Are The Most Popular Teams in Asia|url=http://www.caughtoffside.com/?referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F#article/caughtoffside-580134|publisher=Caughtoffside|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nBeing reputed as the most-hated club in the country has been embraced by the club and its fans, with the phrase ''\"\u00d3diame M\u00e1s\"''&nbsp;\u2013 or \"Hate me more\" in English&nbsp;\u2013 being known as one of the team's unofficial slogans.<ref>{{cite web|last=French|first=Scott|title=Fandom taken to a different level at Club America|url=http://www.espn.go.com/general/story?storyId=5085080&city=losangeles&src=desktop|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=April 28, 2010}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAm\u00e9rica has the highest attendance numbers in Mexico and the eighth most in the world.<ref name=\"billsportsmaps1\">{{cite web|url=http://billsportsmaps.com/?p=22541 |title=2011\u201312 World Football Attendances&nbsp;\u2013 Best Drawing Leagues (Chart of Top-20-drawing national leagues of association football) / Plus list of 35-highest drawing association football clubs in the world in 2011\u201312.}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\nAdditional club sponsors and partners:<ref>{{cite web|title=Gu\u00eda de medios|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/pdf/guia-de-medios-ap2015.pdf|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928133224/http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/pdf/guia-de-medios-ap2015.pdf|archivedate=28 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Campos|first=Alan|title=Los grandes del patrocinio|url=http://www.merca20.com/77496/|publisher=Merca2.0|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Bridgestone]]\n*[[Calvin Klein]]<ref>{{cite web|date=11 September 2014|title=Calvin Klein vestir\u00e1 al Am\u00e9rica|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/noticias/2014/09/11/calvin-klein-vestira-al-america|publisher=Medio Tiempo|accessdate=11 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912052659/http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/mexico/noticias/2014/09/11/calvin-klein-vestira-al-america|archivedate=12 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*[[Coca-Cola]]\n*[[Corona (beer)|Corona]]\n*[[The Home Depot]]\n*[[Interjet]]\n*[[Powerade]]\n*[[StubHub]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Club America \u2013 StubHub |url=https://www.stubhub.com/club-america-tickets/performer/323486/ |website=StubHub.com}}</ref>\n*[[Total S.A.|Total]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Bienvenido TOTAL|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/comunicados/bienvenido-total/|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Sitio Oficial}}</ref>\n*[[Toyota]]\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Management===\n[[File:Emilio Azc\u00e1rraga Jean.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Since 2011, [[Emilio Azc\u00e1rraga Jean]] serves as the chairman of Grupo Televisa's Committee of Football.]]\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position\n! Staff\n|-\n|Chairman||[[Emilio Azc\u00e1rraga Jean]]\n|-\n|Honorary counsel||Bernardo G\u00f3mez Mart\u00ednez\n|-\n|Sporting president||[[Santiago Ba\u00f1os]]\n|-\n|-\n|Director of operations||''Vacant''\n|-\n|Coordinator of strategic planning||Miguel \u00c1ngel Garza\n|-\n|Academy director||[[Alfredo Tena]]\n|-\n|Academy operations coordinator||Carlos Valenzuela\n|-\n|Director of communications and marketing||Quentin Paquelier\n|-\n|Director of public relations||Karina Mora\n|}\n\nSource: [http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/club-america/organigrama Club Am\u00e9rica]\n\n===Coaching staff===\n[[File:PiojoHerrera.jpg|right|thumb|upright|[[Miguel Herrera]] is the current manager of the club.]]\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position\n! Staff\n|-\n|Manager||[[Miguel Herrera]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Assistant managers||[[Gilberto Adame]]\n|-\n|Oscar Escobar\n|-\n|\u00c1lvaro Galindo\n|-\n|Goalkeeper coach||Jos\u00e9 Torruco\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Fitness coaches||Giber Becerra\n|-\n|Jos\u00e9 Rangel\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Physiotherapists||Christian Motta\n|-\n|Carlos Henrique Pecanha\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Team doctors\n|Alfonso D\u00edaz\n|-\n|Jos\u00e9 Guadalupe V\u00e1zquez\n|}\n\nSource: [http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/primer-equipo/cuerpo-tecnico Club Am\u00e9rica]\n\n==Players==\n{{For|a list of all former and current Am\u00e9rica players with a Wikipedia article|Category:Club Am\u00e9rica footballers}}\n\n===First-team squad===\n{{updated|12 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Plantilla|url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/plantilla/club-america/|publisher=Club Am\u00e9rica&nbsp;\u2013 Siti\u00f3 Oficial}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Squad|url=http://ligamx.net/cancha/club/1/america|website=Liga MX.net}}</ref>\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=2|nat=MEX|name=[[Luis Fernando Fuentes|Luis Fuentes]]|pos=DF|other=on loan from [[Club Tijuana|Tijuana]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=3|nat=MEX|name=[[Jorge Eduardo S\u00e1nchez|Jorge S\u00e1nchez]]|pos=DF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|nat=URU|name=[[Sebasti\u00e1n C\u00e1ceres]]|pos=DF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|nat=ARG|name=[[Santiago C\u00e1seres]]|pos=MF|other=on loan from [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=6|nat=MEX|name=[[Guillermo Ochoa]]|pos=GK|other=[[captain (association football)#Club|vice-captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|nat=ARG|name=[[Leonardo Su\u00e1rez]]|pos=MF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|nat=MEX|name=[[Alonso Escoboza]]|pos=DF|other=on loan from [[Club Tijuana|Tijuana]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|nat=COL|name=[[Roger Mart\u00ednez]]|pos=FW|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=MEX|name=[[Giovani dos Santos]]|pos=MF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=COL|name=[[Andr\u00e9s Ibarg\u00fcen]]|pos=MF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=COL|name=[[Nicol\u00e1s Benedetti]]|pos=MF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=CHI|name=[[Nicol\u00e1s Castillo]]|pos=FW|other=}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|nat=MEX|name=[[Sebasti\u00e1n C\u00f3rdova]]|pos=MF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=PAR|name=[[Bruno Valdez]]|pos=DF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|nat=ARG|name=[[Emanuel Aguilera]]|pos=DF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|nat=PAR|name=[[Richard S\u00e1nchez (Paraguayan footballer)|Richard S\u00e1nchez]]|pos=MF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|nat=MEX|name=[[Henry Mart\u00edn]]|pos=FW|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|nat=MEX|name=[[Paul Aguilar]]|pos=DF|other=[[Club captain|captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=MEX|name=[[Antonio de Jes\u00fas L\u00f3pez|Antonio L\u00f3pez]]|pos=MF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|nat=URU|name=[[Federico Vi\u00f1as]]|pos=FW|other=on loan from [[Juventud de Las Piedras|Juventud]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|nat=MEX|name=[[Fernando Gonz\u00e1lez (footballer, born 1994)|Rub\u00e9n Gonz\u00e1lez]]|pos=MF|other=}}\n{{Fs player|no=